{"title_page": "Joy J. Johnson", "text_new": "{{Infobox state representative\n|name         = Joy Joseph Johnson\n|image        = \n|image_size=180px\n|office=Member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]]\n|term_start   =1971\n|term_end     =1979\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date         = \n|birth_place        =\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = December 30, 1996\n|party              = \n|occupation= Baptist Minister\n|spouse             =\n|children           =\n|relations=\n|residence= [[Fairmont, North Carolina]]\n|alma_mater=\n}}\nRev. '''Joy Joseph Johnson''' (died December 30, 1996) was an African-American Baptist minister and politician from [[North Carolina]]. Johnson was the second African-American member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]] since the passage of the [[Voting Rights Act]]. Johnson followed Rep. [[Henry E. Frye]] and served from 1971\u20131979. He the ninth pastor of the First Baptist Church in [[Fairmont, North Carolina]].<ref>http://www.firstbaptistfairmontnorth.org/page/weve_come_this_far_by_faith</ref> He represented [[Robeson County, North Carolina]] in the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"Jordan\">{{cite news|url=https://nccppr.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Black_Legislators-From_Political_Novelty_to_Political_Force.pdf|title=Black Legislators: From Political Novelty to Political Force|last=Jordan|first=Milton C.|date=December 1989|work=North Carolina Insight Magazine|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Joy J}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Fairmont, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:Baptists from North Carolina]]\n\n\n{{NorthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox state representative\n|name         = Joy Joseph Johnson\n|image        = \n|image_size=180px\n|office=Member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]]\n|term_start   =1971\n|term_end     =1979\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date         = \n|birth_place        =\n|death_date         = \n|death_place        = December 30, 1996\n|party              = \n|occupation= Baptist Minister\n|spouse             =\n|children           =\n|relations=\n|residence= [[Fairmont, North Carolina]]\n|alma_mater=\n}}\nRev. '''Joy Joseph Johnson''' (died December 30, 1996) was an African-American Baptist minister and politician from [[North Carolina]]. Johnson was the second African-American member of the [[North Carolina House of Representatives]] since the passage of the [[Voting Rights Act]]. Johnson followed Rep. [[Henry E. Frye]] and served from 1971-1979. He the ninth pastor of the First Baptist Church in [[Fairmont, North Carolina]].<ref>http://www.firstbaptistfairmontnorth.org/page/weve_come_this_far_by_faith</ref> He represented [[Robeson County, North Carolina]] in the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"Jordan\">{{cite news|url=https://nccppr.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Black_Legislators-From_Political_Novelty_to_Political_Force.pdf|title=Black Legislators: From Political Novelty to Political Force|last=Jordan|first=Milton C.|date=December 1989|work=North Carolina Insight Magazine|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Joy J}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Fairmont, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:Baptists from North Carolina]]\n\n\n{{NorthCarolina-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1971-1979 \u2192 1971\u20131979", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joy_J._Johnson"}
{"title_page": "Alyce Spotted Bear", "text_new": "'''Alyce Spotted Bear''' (December 17, 1945 &ndash; August 13, 2013) was an [[United States|American]] educator and politician.\n\nBorn in Elbowoods on the [[Fort Berthold Reservation]] of the [[Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara Nation]], [[North Dakota]], Spotted Bear received her bachelor's degree from [[Dickinson, North Dakota]], her masters from [[Pennsylvania State University]], and studied for her doctorate at [[Cornell University]]. Spotted Bear served as chairman of the Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara Tribe 1982\u20131987. She was vice president and instructor at the [[Fort Berthold Community College]]. In 2010, President [[Barack Obama]] appointed Spotted Bear to the National Advisory Committee on Indian Education. She died in [[Bismarck, North Dakota]] of cancer.<ref>'Alyce Spotted Bear, tribal leader and Obama appointee, remembered as inspiration' '''Bismarck Tribune (North Dakota),''' Hannah Johnson, August 16, 2013</ref><ref>[http://buffalosfire.com/obituary-alyce-spotted-bear-dec-17-1945-aug-13-2013-2/ Obituary-Alyce Spotted Bear] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102192352/http://buffalosfire.com/obituary-alyce-spotted-bear-dec-17-1945-aug-13-2013-2/ |date=2015-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spotted Bear, Alyce}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from McLean County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Female Native American leaders]]\n[[Category:Dickinson State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Educators from North Dakota]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Alyce Spotted Bear''' (December 17, 1945 &ndash; August 13, 2013) was an [[United States|American]] educator and politician.\n\nBorn in Elbowoods on the [[Fort Berthold Reservation]] of the [[Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara Nation]], [[North Dakota]], Spotted Bear received her bachelor's degree from [[Dickinson, North Dakota]], her masters from [[Pennsylvania State University]], and studied for her doctorate at [[Cornell University]]. Spotted Bear served as chairman of the Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara Tribe 1982-1987. She was vice president and instructor at the [[Fort Berthold Community College]]. In 2010, President [[Barack Obama]] appointed Spotted Bear to the National Advisory Committee on Indian Education. She died in [[Bismarck, North Dakota]] of cancer.<ref>'Alyce Spotted Bear, tribal leader and Obama appointee, remembered as inspiration' '''Bismarck Tribune (North Dakota),''' Hannah Johnson, August 16, 2013</ref><ref>[http://buffalosfire.com/obituary-alyce-spotted-bear-dec-17-1945-aug-13-2013-2/ Obituary-Alyce Spotted Bear] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102192352/http://buffalosfire.com/obituary-alyce-spotted-bear-dec-17-1945-aug-13-2013-2/ |date=2015-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spotted Bear, Alyce}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from McLean County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Female Native American leaders]]\n[[Category:Dickinson State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Educators from North Dakota]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1982-1987 \u2192 1982\u20131987", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alyce_Spotted_Bear"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Moulton (soldier)", "text_new": "[[Image:Stephen Moulton 33.GIF|thumb|right|250px|Stephen Moulton]]\n\nLt. Col. '''Stephen Moulton''' and his sons fought in one of the most pivotal battles of the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\nFighting a rear guard action for three days as [[George Washington]] directed the American retreat from [[Battle of Long Island|Long Island]], Moulton and three of his sons were finally captured on September 15, 1775.  Moulton and his sons, all officers, were detained as prisoners of war by [[General Howe]]\u2019s Adjutant in the notorious [[Sugar house prisons (New York)|Sugar House Prison]]<ref>[http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/patriotprisons/sugarjail.html Sugar House Prison Window]. Correctionhistory.org (1908-11-18). Retrieved on 2010-09-20.</ref> in [[New York City]]. After being held for five months by General Howe's forces, Moulton and his sons were exchanged for British officers held by General Washington's staff in March 1777.\n\n==Further reading==\nLt. Colonel Moulton's service is chronicled in the official history of Floyd, New York<ref>[http://oneida.nygenweb.net/misc/wager/ch34.html Our County and {{sic|It|'s|nolink=y}} People] Retrieved on 2010-09-20.</ref> and documented on page 88 of the New York Revolutionary War Census of Pensioners for Revolutionary Military Services, published in 1841 in Washington, DC. (195p).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moulton, Stephen}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Continental Army officers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War prisoners of war held by Great Britain]]\n\n\n{{NorthAm-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Stephen Moulton 33.GIF|thumb|right|250px|Stephen Moulton]]\n\nLt. Col. '''Stephen Moulton''' and his sons fought in one of the most pivotal battles of the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\nFighting a rear guard action for three days as [[George Washington]] directed the American retreat from [[Battle of Long Island|Long Island]], Moulton and three of his sons were finally captured on September 15, 1775.  Moulton and his sons, all officers, were detained as prisoners of war by [[General Howe]]\u2019s Adjutant in the notorious [[Sugar house prisons (New York)|Sugar House Prison]]<ref>[http://www.correctionhistory.org/html/chronicl/patriotprisons/sugarjail.html Sugar House Prison Window]. Correctionhistory.org (1908-11-18). Retrieved on 2010-09-20.</ref> in [[New York City]]. After being held for five months by General Howe's forces, Moulton and his sons were exchanged for British officers held by General Washington's staff in March 1777.\n\n==Further reading==\nLt. Colonel Moulton's service is chronicled in the official history of Floyd, New York<ref>[http://oneida.nygenweb.net/misc/wager/ch34.html Our County and It's People] Retrieved on 2010-09-20.</ref> and documented on page 88 of the New York Revolutionary War Census of Pensioners for Revolutionary Military Services, published in 1841 in Washington, DC. (195p).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moulton, Stephen}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Continental Army officers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War prisoners of war held by Great Britain]]\n\n\n{{NorthAm-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:add sic template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Moulton_(soldier)"}
{"title_page": "Ray Schnell", "text_new": "'''Raphael \"Ray\" Schnell''' (May 1, 1893 \u2013 April 5, 1970) was a [[North Dakota Republican Party]] politician who served as the 23rd [[List of Lieutenant Governors of North Dakota|Lieutenant Governor]] of [[North Dakota]] from 1951 to 1953 under Governor [[Clarence Norman Brunsdale]]. Schnell also served in the [[North Dakota House]] from 1939 to 1940, 1943\u20131946, and 1963\u20131964.<ref>North Dakota Blue Book, 1989</ref> Schnell died in 1970 of cancer at age 77.<ref>[https://news.google.com/archivesearch?q=%22ray+schnell%22&btnG=Search+Archives&hl=en&ned=us&as_ldate=1970&as_hdate=1970 Article on Schnell's death]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Clarence P. Dahl]]\n|title=[[List of Lieutenant Governors of North Dakota|Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]\n|years=1951&ndash;1953\n|after=Clarence P. Dahl\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of North Dakota |expanded=Lt. Governors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schnell, Ray}}\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of North Dakota]]\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the North Dakota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Raphael \"Ray\" Schnell''' (May 1, 1893 \u2013 April 5, 1970) was a [[North Dakota Republican Party]] politician who served as the 23rd [[List of Lieutenant Governors of North Dakota|Lieutenant Governor]] of [[North Dakota]] from 1951 to 1953 under Governor [[Clarence Norman Brunsdale]]. Schnell also served in the [[North Dakota House]] from 1939 to 1940, 1943\u20131946, and 1963-1964.<ref>North Dakota Blue Book, 1989</ref> Schnell died in 1970 of cancer at age 77.<ref>[https://news.google.com/archivesearch?q=%22ray+schnell%22&btnG=Search+Archives&hl=en&ned=us&as_ldate=1970&as_hdate=1970 Article on Schnell's death]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{