{"title_page": "Rolland W. Redlin", "text_new": "[[File:Rolland W. Redlin.jpg|thumb|right|Rolland W. Redlin]]\n'''Rolland W. \"Rollie\" Redlin''' (February 29, 1920 &ndash; September 23, 2011) was a [[U.S. Representative]] from [[North Dakota]], who served between 1965 and 1967. He also served in the [[North Dakota Senate]] from 1959 to 1963 and later returned to serve again from 1973 until his retirement in 2000, as Senate President Pro Tempore 1987\u20139, and Minority Leadership later during his final 27 years' service. A member of the [[Democratic-NPL]], he lived near [[Minot, North Dakota]] until 2009, when he moved to Rapid City, SD, to be closer to family members.\n\nIn 1964, he ran for the U.S. House of Representatives and won, unseating incumbent Republican [[Don L. Short]].  He was the first Democratic Representative to represent Western North Dakota.<ref>{{cite news|first=D. J. R.|last=Bruckner|title=North Dakota Democrat Has Strong Opposition|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=A4|date=October 27, 1966}}</ref> In 1966, he was defeated for reelection by former Bismarck Mayor [[Thomas Kleppe]].  Redlin ran again in 1968 but lost by a narrow margin. He has stated his vote for the 1965 Voting Rights Act was the accomplishment while serving in the US House of Representatives of which he is most proud, and that the breakdown of civil discourse in American politics during the past two decades is perhaps his greatest disappointment.\n\nRedlin died on September 23, 2011, at his home in Rapid City. He was 91.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/lifestyles/announcements/obituaries/rolland-redlin/article_4d84efc6-e6f4-11e0-93b5-001cc4c03286.html|title=Rolland Redlin|newspaper=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|date=September 25, 2011|accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CongBio|R000107}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box|state=North Dakota|district=2|before=[[Don L. Short]]|after=[[Thomas S. Kleppe]]|years=1965\u20131967}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NorthDakotaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redlin, Rolland W.}}\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from North Dakota]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents pro tempore of the North Dakota Senate]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Ward County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Rolland W. Redlin.jpg|thumb|right|Rolland W. Redlin]]\n'''Rolland W. \"Rollie\" Redlin''' (February 29, 1920 &ndash; September 23, 2011) was a [[U.S. Representative]] from [[North Dakota]], who served between 1965 and 1967. He also served in the [[North Dakota Senate]] from 1959 to 1963 and later returned to serve again from 1973 until his retirement in 2000, as Senate President Pro Tempore 1987-9, and Minority Leadership later during his final 27 years' service. A member of the [[Democratic-NPL]], he lived near [[Minot, North Dakota]] until 2009, when he moved to Rapid City, SD, to be closer to family members.\n\nIn 1964, he ran for the U.S. House of Representatives and won, unseating incumbent Republican [[Don L. Short]].  He was the first Democratic Representative to represent Western North Dakota.<ref>{{cite news|first=D. J. R.|last=Bruckner|title=North Dakota Democrat Has Strong Opposition|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=A4|date=October 27, 1966}}</ref> In 1966, he was defeated for reelection by former Bismarck Mayor [[Thomas Kleppe]].  Redlin ran again in 1968 but lost by a narrow margin. He has stated his vote for the 1965 Voting Rights Act was the accomplishment while serving in the US House of Representatives of which he is most proud, and that the breakdown of civil discourse in American politics during the past two decades is perhaps his greatest disappointment.\n\nRedlin died on September 23, 2011, at his home in Rapid City. He was 91.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/lifestyles/announcements/obituaries/rolland-redlin/article_4d84efc6-e6f4-11e0-93b5-001cc4c03286.html|title=Rolland Redlin|newspaper=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|date=September 25, 2011|accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CongBio|R000107}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box|state=North Dakota|district=2|before=[[Don L. Short]]|after=[[Thomas S. Kleppe]]|years=1965\u20131967}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NorthDakotaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redlin, Rolland W.}}\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from North Dakota]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents pro tempore of the North Dakota Senate]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Ward County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1987-9 \u2192 1987\u20139", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolland_W._Redlin"}
