{"title_page": "Keith Kempenich", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name         =Keith Kempenich\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| state_house  = North Dakota\n| district     = 39th\n| term_start   =1993\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| prior_term   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1959|7|28}}\n| birth_place  =[[Bowman, North Dakota]], United States\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| profession   = \n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Keith Kempenich''' (born July 28, 1958) is an [[American people|American]] politician. He is a member of the [[North Dakota House of Representatives]] from the 39th District, serving since 1992. He is a member of the Republican party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keith Kempenich|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/7735/keith-kempenich|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Legislation ==\n{{expand section|date=January 2017}}\nIn January 2017, Kempenich proposed a bill titled HB No. 1203 which would prevent a driver who unintentionally injures or kills a person intentionally obstructing a roadway from being held liable for any damages.<ref>North Dakota HOUSE BILL NO. 1203 http://www.legis.nd.gov/assembly/65-2017/documents/17-0351-01000.pdf</ref> He said the bill was in response to the [[Dakota Access Pipeline protests]] blocking a nearby highway.<ref>Brooks, Jennifer. \"North Dakota Bill Aimed At Standing Rock Protest\". Star Tribune, 2017, http://www.startribune.com/north-dakota-bill-aimed-at-standing-rock-protest/410860535/.</ref> It was cosponsored by other state representatives and senators, and drew criticism on the grounds that it would violate the First Amendment rights of protestors. Opponents said it would effectively legalize running over protesters on the road, as long as [[intention (criminal law)|criminal intent]] cannot be demonstrated on the part of the driver. <ref>Agrawal, Nina. In North Dakota, it would be legal to hit a protester with your car. latimes.com (2017). at <http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-bills-protest-criminal-20170201-story.html></ref> The bill was defeated by a 50\u201341 vote on February 13.<ref>[http://www.westfargopioneer.com/news/4217408-driver-liability-bill-defeated-north-dakota-house \"Driver liability bill defeated in North Dakota House\", by John Hageman, ''West Fargo Pioneer'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{North Dakota House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kempenich, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the North Dakota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name         =Keith Kempenich\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| state_house  = North Dakota\n| district     = 39th\n| term_start   =1993\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| prior_term   =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1959|7|28}}\n| birth_place  =[[Bowman, North Dakota]], United States\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| profession   = \n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Keith Kempenich''' (born July 28, 1958) is an [[American people|American]] politician. He is a member of the [[North Dakota House of Representatives]] from the 39th District, serving since 1992. He is a member of the Republican party.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keith Kempenich|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/7735/keith-kempenich|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Legislation ==\n{{expand section|date=January 2017}}\nIn January 2017, Kempenich proposed a bill titled HB No. 1203 which would prevent a driver who unintentionally injures or kills a person intentionally obstructing a roadway from being held liable for any damages.<ref>North Dakota HOUSE BILL NO. 1203 http://www.legis.nd.gov/assembly/65-2017/documents/17-0351-01000.pdf</ref> He said the bill was in response to the [[Dakota Access Pipeline protests]] blocking a nearby highway.<ref>Brooks, Jennifer. \"North Dakota Bill Aimed At Standing Rock Protest\". Star Tribune, 2017, http://www.startribune.com/north-dakota-bill-aimed-at-standing-rock-protest/410860535/.</ref> It was cosponsored by other state representatives and senators, and drew criticism on the grounds that it would violate the First Amendment rights of protestors. Opponents said it would effectively legalize running over protesters on the road, as long as [[intention (criminal law)|criminal intent]] cannot be demonstrated on the part of the driver. <ref>Agrawal, Nina. In North Dakota, it would be legal to hit a protester with your car. latimes.com (2017). at <http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-bills-protest-criminal-20170201-story.html></ref> The bill was defeated by a 50-41 vote on February 13.<ref>[http://www.westfargopioneer.com/news/4217408-driver-liability-bill-defeated-north-dakota-house \"Driver liability bill defeated in North Dakota House\", by John Hageman, ''West Fargo Pioneer'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{North Dakota House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kempenich, Keith}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the North Dakota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegislation:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 50-41 \u2192 50\u201341", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Kempenich"}
{"title_page": "Roger Johnson (politician)", "text_new": "{{For|other politicians of this name|Roger Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image        =\n|name         = Roger Johnson\n|caption      = \n|office       = 14th President of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]] \n|term_start   = 2009\n|term_end     = incumbent\n|predecessor  = [[Tom Buis]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = 5th [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]]\n|term_start1  = 1996\n|term_end1    = April 6, 2009\n|governor1    = [[Ed Schafer]]<br>[[John Hoeven]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Sarah Vogel]]\n|successor1   = [[Doug Goehring]]\n|birth_date   = \n|party        = [[North Dakota Democratic-NPL Party|Democratic]]\n|residence    = [[Turtle Lake, North Dakota]]\n}}\n'''Roger Johnson''', is president of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]], and the immediate past [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]].<ref>[http://www.nd.gov/ndda/about-us/department-history Department history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216004740/http://www.nd.gov/ndda/about-us/department-history |date=2015-02-16 }}</ref> He is a member of the [[North Dakota Democratic-NPL Party]]. As of 2016, he is the most recent statewide elected Democrat to serve in the North Dakota state government.\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nJohnson grew up on a farm in Turtle Lake, North Dakota.<ref>[http://www.nfu.org/about-us/staff/roger-johnson Roger Johnson] Retrieved June 3, 2010</ref> He earned a BA from [[North Dakota State University]] in 1975 and did graduate work for two years. He then started farming, while working as a farm credit counselor. In 1988 he was asked by [[Sarah Vogel]], the Agriculture Commissioner at the time, to work for her and run the state's Agricultural Mediation Program, which helped farmers resolve financial problems with creditors. He resigned in 1996, when he ran for [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]].\n\n==Political career==\nJohnson was first elected Agriculture Commissioner in 1996 and re-elected in 2000, 2004, and 2006. The election in 1996 was one of the closest in North Dakota history. Johnson earned 129,423 votes, while GOP candidate [[Dina Butcher]] earned 129,140 votes.<ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Abstracts%20by%20Year/1990s'%20Election%20Results/1996/General%20Election%2011-05-1996.pdf Retrieved June 30, 2009</ref> He ran against [[Clare Carlson]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Evenson|first=Samantha|title=Trump Administration Appoints Clare Carlson to Serve as State Director for USDA Rural Development in North Dakota|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=[[USDA Rural Development]]|accessdate=June 17, 2019|url=https://www.rd.usda.gov/newsroom/news-release/trump-administration-appoints-clare-carlson-serve-state-director-usda-rural}}</ref> He ran against GOP candidate [[Doug Goehring]] in 2004, winning by a little over 1,800 votes. Goehring did not demand a recount.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/no-recount-in-ag-commissioner-race/article_0a91596a-d22d-511b-a066-df527f76c21a.html|title=No recount in ag commissioner race|newspaper=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|date=November 3, 2004|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref> Johnson faced a rematch against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Goehring in the 2006 election, winning by a wider margin than in 2004. He resigned as Agriculture Commissioner in 2009 to become president of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandforksherald.com/content/nd-ag-commissioner-johnson-submits-resignation-letter|title=N.D. ag commissioner Johnson submits resignation letter|newspaper=[[Grand Forks Herald]]|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the president of the [[National Association of State Departments of Agriculture]] (NASDA) from 2007\u20132008. While president, Johnson helped craft the 2008 Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfu.org/about-nfu/leadership/roger-johnson|title=Roger Johnson|publisher=[[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]]|accessdate=March 4, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315105557/http://nfu.org/about-nfu/leadership/roger-johnson|archivedate=March 15, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Sarah Vogel]]|title=[[List of Agriculture Commissioners of North Dakota|Agriculture Commissioner of North Dakota]]|years=1997&ndash;2009|after=[[Doug Goehring]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NDAgcommissioners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Roger}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Commissioners of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from McLean County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:North Dakota State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|other politicians of this name|Roger Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image        =\n|name         = Roger Johnson\n|caption      = \n|office       = 14th President of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]] \n|term_start   = 2009\n|term_end     = incumbent\n|predecessor  = [[Tom Buis]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = 5th [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]]\n|term_start1  = 1996\n|term_end1    = April 6, 2009\n|governor1    = [[Ed Schafer]]<br>[[John Hoeven]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Sarah Vogel]]\n|successor1   = [[Doug Goehring]]\n|birth_date   = \n|party        = [[North Dakota Democratic-NPL Party|Democratic]]\n|residence    = [[Turtle Lake, North Dakota]]\n}}\n'''Roger Johnson''', is president of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]], and the immediate past [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]].<ref>[http://www.nd.gov/ndda/about-us/department-history Department history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216004740/http://www.nd.gov/ndda/about-us/department-history |date=2015-02-16 }}</ref> He is a member of the [[North Dakota Democratic-NPL Party]]. As of 2016, he is the most recent statewide elected Democrat to serve in the North Dakota state government.\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nJohnson grew up on a farm in Turtle Lake, North Dakota.<ref>[http://www.nfu.org/about-us/staff/roger-johnson Roger Johnson] Retrieved June 3, 2010</ref> He earned a BA from [[North Dakota State University]] in 1975 and did graduate work for two years. He then started farming, while working as a farm credit counselor. In 1988 he was asked by [[Sarah Vogel]], the Agriculture Commissioner at the time, to work for her and run the state\u2019s Agricultural Mediation Program, which helped farmers resolve financial problems with creditors. He resigned in 1996, when he ran for [[North Dakota Agriculture Commissioner]].\n\n==Political career==\nJohnson was first elected Agriculture Commissioner in 1996 and re-elected in 2000, 2004, and 2006. The election in 1996 was one of the closest in North Dakota history. Johnson earned 129,423 votes, while GOP candidate [[Dina Butcher]] earned 129,140 votes.<ref>https://vip.sos.nd.gov/pdfs/Abstracts%20by%20Year/1990s'%20Election%20Results/1996/General%20Election%2011-05-1996.pdf Retrieved June 30, 2009</ref> He ran against [[Clare Carlson]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Evenson|first=Samantha|title=Trump Administration Appoints Clare Carlson to Serve as State Director for USDA Rural Development in North Dakota|date=December 6, 2017|publisher=[[USDA Rural Development]]|accessdate=June 17, 2019|url=https://www.rd.usda.gov/newsroom/news-release/trump-administration-appoints-clare-carlson-serve-state-director-usda-rural}}</ref> He ran against GOP candidate [[Doug Goehring]] in 2004, winning by a little over 1,800 votes. Goehring did not demand a recount.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/no-recount-in-ag-commissioner-race/article_0a91596a-d22d-511b-a066-df527f76c21a.html|title=No recount in ag commissioner race|newspaper=[[The Bismarck Tribune]]|date=November 3, 2004|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref> Johnson faced a rematch against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Goehring in the 2006 election, winning by a wider margin than in 2004. He resigned as Agriculture Commissioner in 2009 to become president of the [[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandforksherald.com/content/nd-ag-commissioner-johnson-submits-resignation-letter|title=N.D. ag commissioner Johnson submits resignation letter|newspaper=[[Grand Forks Herald]]|accessdate=February 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the president of the [[National Association of State Departments of Agriculture]] (NASDA) from 2007-2008. While president, Johnson helped craft the 2008 Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfu.org/about-nfu/leadership/roger-johnson|title=Roger Johnson|publisher=[[National Farmers Union (United States)|National Farmers Union]]|accessdate=March 4, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315105557/http://nfu.org/about-nfu/leadership/roger-johnson|archivedate=March 15, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Sarah Vogel]]|title=[[List of Agriculture Commissioners of North Dakota|Agriculture Commissioner of North Dakota]]|years=1997&ndash;2009|after=[[Doug Goehring]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NDAgcommissioners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Roger}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Commissioners of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from McLean County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:North Dakota State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 2007-2008 \u2192 2007\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Johnson_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Martial law in Poland", "text_new": "{{short description|Coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Martial law in Poland\n| place       = {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Poland]]\n| partof      = the [[Soviet reaction to the Polish crisis of 1980\u20131981]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon|Polish People's Republic}} [[Polish People's Republic]]\n* [[Polish People's Army]]\n* [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia (MO)]]\n* [[ZOMO]]\n* [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Service (SB)]]\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|Soviet Union}} ({{small|Intelligence support and military equipment}})\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|}} [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity Movement]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]] <br><small>(from 1982)</small>\n* Protesters\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|United States}} ({{small|Financial support}})\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = \n*91 killed\n*Thousands arrested\n| commander1  = [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] \n* [[Czes\u0142aw Kiszczak]]\n| commander2  = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n*[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Frasyniuk]]\n| image       = File:T-55A Martial law Poland.jpg\n| image_size  = 280px\n| caption     = A column of Polish [[T-55]] tanks enters the town of [[Zb\u0105szy\u0144]] while moving east towards the city of [[Pozna\u0144]], 13 December 1981\n| date        = 13 December 1981 \u2013 22 July 1983\n({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=12|day1=13|year1=1981|month2=07|day2=22|year2=1983}})\n| result      = Decisive Polish government victory\n*Crackdown on opposition\n*Protests suppressed \n*Deepened economic crisis\n*Continued resistance until 1989\n| strength1   ='''Initial strength''':<ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref>\n*80,000 soldiers\n*30,000 policemen\n*1,750 tanks\n*1,900 combat vehicles\n*9,000 cars\n| strength2   = ~ 10 million (1981)\n}}\n\n'''Martial law in Poland''' ({{lang-pl|Stan wojenny w Polsce}}) refers to the period between 13 December 1981 and 22 July 1983, when the [[authoritarian]] [[communist government]] of the [[Polish People's Republic]] drastically restricted normal life by introducing [[martial law]] and a [[military junta]] in an attempt to throttle political opposition, in particular the [[Solidarity Movement]]. Thousands of opposition activists were [[Internment|imprisoned]] without charge and as many as 91 killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref> Although martial law was lifted in 1983, many of the [[political prisoner]]s were not released until a general [[amnesty]] in 1986.\n\nSince the 1970s, communist Poland was in a deep [[economic recession]]. The First Secretary [[Edward Gierek]] made large incessant loans from western creditors to achieve a better economic output that instead resulted in a domestic crisis. Basic goods were being heavily [[Rationing|rationed]] which acted as a stimuli for the establishment of a first anti-communist [[trade union]] in the [[Eastern Bloc]], known as Solidarity, in 1980. Gierek, who permitted the trade union to appear per the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]], was dismissed from his post less than a month later under pressure from the USSR and confined to [[house arrest]]. Poland's already somewhat liberal policies concerning the opposition were worrisome for hardliners in the [[Soviet Union]], who feared that the Poles may overthrow communism and ally themselves with the [[Western Bloc]]. The Soviets were particularly uneasy as the departure of Eastern Bloc's most populous nation from [[Comecon]] would trigger further financial and economic problems that would bring an end to communist rule in Central-Eastern Europe. After a series of strikes and demonstrations by employees of chief industrial regions, Poland was directly heading towards bankruptcy. \n\nThe [[Military Council of National Salvation]] was formed by the new First Secretary of the Polish United Workers' Party, General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], who was determined to put an end to the demonstrations and crush the opposition by force if necessary. There is speculation whether Jaruzelski instigated martial law to prevent bloodshed if the Soviets and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries were to enter Poland under the mutual assistance treaty, like in the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] and the [[invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968]]. On 13 December 1981, Jaruzelski announced the introduction of martial law in a televised speech addressed to the entire nation. The Polish People's Army, [[Citizen's Militia]] (MO), [[ZOMO]] special units and tanks rolled onto the streets to scare off demonstrators, begin regular patrols and maintain [[curfew]]. Intercity travelling was forbidden unless a permit was granted by the authorities, food shortages intensified and censorship was placed on all media and [[post]]. The [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|secret services (SB)]] [[wiretapped]] phones in public booths and state institutions. \n\nOn 16 December, pro-Solidarity miners organized a strike against the declaration of the martial law at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]]. The ZOMO squads, nicknamed \"Communist [[Gestapo]]\" by the opposition, brutally [[Pacification of Wujek|pacified Wujek]], which resulted in the deaths of 9 miners. All other [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|demonstrations across Poland]] were met with armed force of the services, which utilized [[water cannons]], [[tear gas]], [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]], truncheons and clubs to disperse crowds and beat protesters. Thousands were detained and some were tortured in state prisons. On 31 August 1982, in the copper-mining town of [[Lubin]], 3 people were mortally wounded by ZOMO. Until the end of the martial law on 22 July 1983, approximately 91 people were killed, though this figure varies and is still debated among historians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\n{{main|History of Poland (1945\u20131989)}}\n===Reforms of Edward Gierek (1970-1975)===\n[[File:Photograph of President Gerald R. Ford, First Secretary Edward Gierek of Poland, and Mrs. Stanislawa Gierek Waving from the Blue Room Balcony during a State Arrival Ceremony - NARA - 7462054.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Gierek in the [[White House]] with President [[Gerald Ford]], 1974]]\nWhen [[Edward Gierek]] succeeded [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka|Gomu\u0142ka]] as the head of state in 1970, he took decisive measures to boost economic growth and develop modern infrastructure. Gierek, a more [[Liberalism|liberal]] figure than his predecessor, was determined to make [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]] the wealthiest and most economically significant communist country of the [[Eastern Bloc]]. However, these ideas prompted resistance from hardline communist leadership as the reform would effectively abandon the fundamental principles of a [[Planned economy|centrally planned]] [[Marxism|Marxist]] economy. The grip and emphasis on state-owned enterprises and state-controlled prices or trade was eventually loosened. Small private businesses began to appear and Poland recorded temporary growth in [[GDP]] and an improvement in living conditions. \n\nGierek maintained close ties with the [[United States]], which he subsequently used for diplomatic and economic purposes. In order to continue with the reforms, large sums of money were borrowed from [[creditors]] in the [[Western Bloc]]. These sequential and uninterrupted loans were primarily targeted at establishing heavy industry, mines or manufacturing facilities that would produce goods for [[export]]. The projected income from the exports would then be used to pay off the [[debt]]. Apart from financing the economic sector, the money was spent on [[social housing]] and on expanding road connections, for example the first fully operational [[highway]] linking Warsaw with industrial [[Silesia]] was opened for traffic in 1976. Furthermore, over 1.8 million [[plattenbau]] flats were constructed to house the growing population. Agricultural output rose by 22% between 1971 and 1975. Gierek also initiated the construction of [[Warszawa Centralna]], Europe's most modern railway station at the time.\n\n===Crisis; debt, rationing and shortages (1976-1981)===\n[[File:Kartka cukier 1kg 07-76.jpg|thumb|left|140px|A ration card for sugar, 1976]]\nAs expenditures increased and debts accumulated, the West would no longer grant Poland loans. Moreover, the [[1973 oil crisis|1973]] and [[1979 oil crisis|1979 oil crises]] affected the fragile economy. Due to previous GDP growth, higher income and expanded industries, the demand for certain goods and [[consumption]] surged. New factories and state enterprises required fuel, materials and a workforce to operate production lines. Soon, the country started exporting locally-produced stock designated for the Polish populace, thus resulting in widespread [[shortages]]. Because the remaining assets were directed at production, exports and debt repayment, the state also reduced imports to minimize expenses. \n\nIn 1976, the communist government introduced [[ration cards]] for sugar, meat, processed food and dairy. Confectionery, [[cocoa]], coffee, rice, [[tobacco]] and other goods not produced in Poland were so heavily rationed that they were almost permanently unavailable. The living standards began to sharply decline; the supply of imported goods was kept to a low minimum and the county was forced to export everything it could, including coal necessary for basic heating and power plants. [[Power outage]]s were commonplace. By 1980, the debt accounted to over US$23 billion, then almost half of Poland's [[nominal GDP]].        \n\n[[File:Jimmy Carter and Edward Gierek First Secretary of Poland - NARA - 177308.tif|thumb|right|230px|[[Edward Gierek]] (right) with President [[Jimmy Carter]] (left) during his state visit to Warsaw, 1977. The loans and Solidarity were among the chief topics discussed]]\n\nAt the same time, the newly-founded [[Solidarity movement]] encouraged farmers to refrain from selling agricultural products (wheat, grain, fruit and others) to the state as a sign of protest. The actual lack of goods on the market and in stores was caused by the fact that production stopped due to the strikes organized by Solidarity. In 1980, the national income fell by 6% compared to previous year, and in 1981 by 12%. The number of exports declined by 4.2%. Mismanagement and wastefulness were abundant. \n\nOn 6 September 1980, Gierek was dismissed from his office, expelled from the Polish United Workers' Party (possibly under the pressure from the Soviet Union) and falsely charged with [[corruption]]. A year later, on 10 September 1981, the Soviet authorities informed the Polish government that in connection with the prevailing situation in Poland the USSR would cut oil supply to Poland by 64% and gas by 47%. The import of [[diesel]] from the Soviet Union was terminated immediately. This action was intended to force the Polish communist authorities to suppress the demonstrations and dissolve Solidarity. The situation was already dire and gradually worsened, which only fueled anti-communist sentiment. A [[civil war]] was hanging by a thread.\n\nIn 1981, Poland notified [[Club de Paris]] (a group of Western-European central banks) about its [[insolvency]], which caught the attention of the entire world.<ref>http://www.clubdeparis.org/en/traitements/poland-27-04-1981/en</ref>\n\n==Introduction, restrictions, patrols==\n===Secret preparations and provocation===\n[[File:Wojciech Jaruzelski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski|Jaruzelski]] was determined to suppress any opposition along with the [[Solidarity Movement]]]]\nAfter the short tenure of [[Stanis\u0142aw Kania]], General and Minister of Defence [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] was chosen as the new First Secretary. Before assuming office, Jaruzelski ordered the Polish General Staff to update plans for a nationwide martial law on 22 October 1980.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> In November 1980, the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Poland)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] planned to potentially facilitate around 12,900 members of the opposition in state prisons and places of internment. \n\nOn 5 December 1980, Kania spoke of the preparations relating to martial law at the [[Warsaw Pact|Warsaw Pact Summit]] in [[Moscow]]. He presented his own view of how to weaken Solidarity and insisted that a \"psychological-operational method\" would be most appropriate to prevent violence. This method entailed strong [[propaganda]] against the movement and deploying [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Services (SB)]] to go undercover and infiltrate Solidarity headquarters in the hope of creating internal conflicts within the opposition. General Jaruzelski was not fully satisfied with the plan, and, in case of failure, already planned radical actions involving the army. Stanis\u0142aw Kania warned [[Brezhnev]] that an armed intervention from the Soviet side to aid Jaruzelski would be met \"with a violent reaction, or even with a national uprising\" that would shake the politics of the Eastern Bloc.     \n\n[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]], chief security advisor to US President [[Jimmy Carter]], stated that \"if the Soviet Union would undertake an armed intervention in Poland, the US would strike back in a [[riposte]] manner\". According to historian and publicist [[Paul Kengor]], the then US President [[Ronald Reagan]] considered sending American troops to Poland to scare off the Soviets.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> This claim was not supported by Brzezinski nor by [[Richard Pipes]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> Kengor then elaborated that Reagan eventually abandoned the plan after he was convinced by his own advisors that the US army stationed across Europe is less capable and much weaker than the Soviet forces.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> \n\n[[File:WieczorWroclawia20marca1981.jpg|thumb|right|240px|A censored regional newspaper that reported about the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which the [[Milicja Obywatelska|Militia]] abused Solidarity members. The censorship was to prevent the slander of state services]] \n\nIn February 1981, the [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Ministry of National Defence]] and Ministry of the Internal Affairs carried out a training scenario, the purpose of which was to explore how martial law will be introduced. The ministries agreed that martial law should be preceded by appropriate propaganda calling for its support, and the decision itself should be based on a pretext that it would bring peace and stability for the society. It was also highlighted that martial law must occur before the fully mobilized [[Fighting Solidarity]] and its allies organize a [[general strike]] that would paralyze the entire country. By March, the situation escalated after the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which local Solidarity delegates invited for a [[National Council (Poland)|Regional National Council]] meeting in [[Bydgoszcz]] to discuss potential strikes were beaten and abused by the [[Citizens' Militia]] (MO). The event, which was to feature in newspapers as a [[provocation]], was concealed by [[censors]]. On 27 March, Solidarity organized a warning strike directed at the government, but, on 30 March, [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] met with [[Mieczys\u0142aw Rakowski]] and a compromise was achieved. The general strike was called off and the situation stabilized for a short period.\n\nIn July, the Soviets increased their military presence in the military base at [[Borne Sulinowo]], where the [[Red Army]] stationed per [[Warsaw Pact]] agreement as in all other [[Eastern Bloc]] countries. Without notifying the Polish authorities, the Soviets unexpectedly sent over 600 tanks to Borne Sulinowo. A month later, commander-in-chief of the Warsaw Pact, [[Viktor Kulikov]], requested that Soviet military advisors are to be placed in the Polish General Staff and assigned to nearly all Polish regiments. It is suspected that Kulikov, acting on behalf of the Soviet Union, was tasked with sending undercover [[KGB]] agents to monitor the situation in Poland from the Polish military's perspective. His request, however, was immediately denied by the Polish government.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref> \n\nOver 25,000 posters announcing martial law were secretly printed in the USSR, transported to Poland by airplane and hidden in the large building housing the Ministry of Internal Affairs.<ref>[[Ryszard Terlecki]]: ''Miecz i tarcza komunizmu. Historia aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa w Polsce 1944-1990'', Krak\u00f3w 2007, p. 270\u2013271.</ref> The full extent of the actions undertaken by Jaruzelski to instigate martial law was not known by even some of the highest notables in the Central Committee of the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] or the Polish [[Sejm]].\n\n===13 December 1981=== \nOn 12 December 1981, shortly before [[midnight]], the [[Polish Council of State]] gathered in Warsaw's [[Belweder Palace]] and approved nationwide martial law.\n\nAt precisely 00:00 hours (12:00 a.m.), the [[ZOMO|Motorized Reserves of the Citizens' Militia]] (ZOMO) began the operation and arrested the first members of Solidarity who were at close reach. In total, between 70,000 and 80,000 soldiers of the People's Army and 30,000 functionaries of the Ministry of Internal Affairs (including SB, ZOMO and the Militia) were deployed for action. Around 1,750 tanks, 1,400 armoured vehicles, 500 militarized transport units, 9000 cars and several [[helicopter]] [[squadron]]s were in service.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> 25% of all units concentrated in the capital, Warsaw, or in surrounding localities.       \n\nAfter the introduction of martial law on 13 December 1981, pro-[[democracy]] movements such as [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] and other smaller organisations were banned, and their leaders, including [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]], jailed overnight. In the morning, thousands of soldiers in military vehicles appeared on the streets of every major city. A [[curfew]] was imposed, the national borders sealed, airports closed, and road access to main cities restricted. Telephone lines were disconnected, mail subject to renewed [[postal censorship]], all independent official organizations were criminalized, and classes in schools and universities suspended.\n\nDuring the initial imposition of martial law, several dozen people were killed. Official reports during the crackdown claimed about a dozen fatalities, while a [[Sejm of the Republic of Poland|parliamentary]] commission in the years 1989\u20131991 arrived at a figure of over 90.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html Ofiary stanu wojennego i lat nast\u0119pnych do 1989] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108144638/http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html |date=2014-01-08 }} by Piotr Lipi\u0144ski</ref> In the deadliest incident, nine coal miners were killed by: \"[[ZOMO]]\" paramilitary police during the [[strike-breaking]] at the [[Pacification of Wujek]] on 16 December 1981. Others were also killed and wounded during a massive second wave of demonstrations on [[August 31, 1982 demonstrations in Poland|31 August 1982]].\n\n[[File:Telegr.jpg|thumb|right|A censored telegram, 1982]]\n\nThe government imposed a six-day work week while the mass media, public services, healthcare services, power stations, coal mines, sea ports, railway stations, and most key factories were placed under military management, with employees having to follow military orders or face a [[court martial]]. As part of the crackdown, media and educational institutions underwent \"verification\", a process that tested each employee's attitude towards the regime and to the Solidarity movement; as a result, thousands of journalists, teachers and professors were banned from their professions. [[Military court]]s were established to bypass the normal court system, to imprison those spreading \"false information\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/special_report/1999/09/99/iron_curtain/timelines/poland_81.stm 1981: Martial law], [[BBC]]</ref> In an attempt to crush resistance, civilian phone lines were routinely tapped and monitored by government agents.\n\nAt the invitation of Jaruzelski, a delegation of the ruling [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party]] visited Poland between 27 and 29 December. The Hungarians shared with their Polish colleagues their experiences on crushing the [[1956 Hungarian revolution|\"counterrevolution\" of 1956]]. Earlier in the autumn of 1981, Polish television had broadcast a special film on the 1956 events in Hungary, showing scenes of rebels hanging security officers etc.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wI9TUaZZeAMC&pg=PA499&dq=jaruzelski+1981+martial+law#v=onepage&q=jaruzelski%201981%20martial%20law&f=false Google Books]</ref>\n\nThe introduction of martial law was enthusiastically supported by some figures on the right like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]],<ref>Polish Western affairs, Volumes 31\u201332. Instytut Zachodni, 1990. [https://books.google.com/books?id=PepBAAAAYAAJ&q=%22jedrzej+giertych%22&dq=%22jedrzej+giertych%22&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CEsQ6AEwCThk p. 165]</ref> who believed Solidarity to be a disguised communist movement dominated by Jewish [[Trotskyite]]s.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:AGAD_Gen._Wojciech_jaruzelski_13_grudnia_1981.png|Jaruzelski in a TV studio announcing the introduction of martial law\nFile:Stan wojenny obwieszczenie.jpg|The proclamation of martial law by the State Council\nFile:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 12a.JPG|Members of the [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia]] race to disperse crowds of protesters\n</gallery>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Kartka P3 11-83.jpeg|thumb|Food, alcohol, and cigarettes [[rationing]] card]]\n\nEven after martial law was lifted, a number of restrictions remained in place for several years that drastically reduced the [[civil liberties]] of the citizenry. It also led to severe economic consequences. The ruling [[military dictatorship]] instituted major price rises (dubbed \"economic reforms\"), which resulted in a fall in real wages of 20% or more. The resulting [[economic crisis]] led to the [[rationing]] of most products and materials, including basic foodstuffs.\n\nAs a consequence of economic hardship and political repression, an exodus of Poles saw 700,000 emigrate to the West between 1981 and 1989.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nypuJ8BARiMC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=poland+economy+1980s&source=bl&ots=iR_fCDeyE6&sig=q2hNTHlJPvd7MOfHIhY-lEKmJsc&hl=en&ei=lLEbS6OKG8z_4Abzt4TnAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=poland%20economy%201980s&f=false Google Books]</ref> \nA number of international flights were even hijacked in attempts to flee the country and its economic problems. Between December 1980 and October 1983, 11 Polish flights were hijacked to [[Berlin Tempelhof Airport]] alone.<ref>[http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 A Symbol Of Allied Solidarity Will Disappear. Berlin - The Atlantic Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707184128/http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a group calling themselves the \"Polish Revolutionary Home Army\" seized the Polish Embassy in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]] on 6 September 1982, taking several diplomats as hostages. However this turned out to be an apparent provocation by the communist Polish secret services aiming to discredit the Solidarity movement.<ref>[http://www.start.umd.edu/start/data/tops/terrorist_organization_profile.asp?id=4206 Terrorist Organization Profile: Polish Revolutionary Home Army]</ref>\n\n==International response==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2009}}\n\nAfter the \"Wujek\" Coal Mine incident in Katowice on 23 December 1981, the [[United States]] imposed [[economic sanctions]] against the [[People's Republic of Poland]]. In 1982 the United States suspended [[most favored nation]] trade status until 1987 and vetoed Poland's application for membership in the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>[http://countrystudies.us/poland/92.htm Poland - The United States]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II wrote a [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/29/world/pope-calls-for-justice-and-peace-in-polish-quest-for-a-settlement.html letter] to the Primate of Poland, Stefan Cardinal Wyszynski, in which he called for peace talks between the state and the workers, supporting the Poles' \"undeniable right to resolve their problems by themselves.\"\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Ruling of unconstitutionality===\nAfter the [[fall of Communism in Poland]] in 1989, members of a parliamentary commission determined that martial law had been imposed in clear violation of the country's [[constitution]] which had authorized the executive to declare martial law only between parliamentary sessions (at other times the decision was to be taken by the [[Sejm]]). However, the Sejm had been in session at the time when martial law was instituted. In 1992 the Sejm declared the 1981 imposition of martial law to be unlawful and unconstitutional.\n\n===Soviet intervention debate===\n{{further|Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981}}\n\nThe instigators of the martial law, such as [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], argue that the army crackdown rescued Poland from a possibly disastrous [[military intervention]] of the [[Soviet Union]], [[East Germany]], and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries (similar to the earlier interventions in [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungary in 1956]] and [[Prague Spring|Czechoslovakia in 1968]]).<ref>[http://www.euronews.net/2008/10/02/jaruzelski-says-martial-law-saved-poland/ Jaruzelski says martial law saved Poland], [[Euronews]], 02/10/08</ref> Public figures who supported the introduction of martial law (including some of the right-wing figures like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]]) would also refer to that threat.\n\nIn 2009, archive documents hinted that in a conversation Jaruzelski had with [[Viktor Kulikov]], a Soviet military leader, Jaruzelski himself begged for Soviet intervention as his domestic control was deteriorating.<ref>[http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php Newpolandexpress.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009161848/http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php |date=2011-10-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_Polands_Jaruzelski_Again_Denies_Seeking_Soviet_Intervention_Against_Solidarity/1902431.html Rferl.org]</ref> Jaruzelski responded by claiming the document was 'just another falsification'.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Declaration script==\nLed by [[General of the Army]] [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (''Wojskowa Rada Ocalenia Narodowego'', WRON) usurped for itself powers reserved for wartime, hence the name. The plan was presented to the government of the [[Soviet Union]] before the declaration in March 1981.\n\nAppearing on Polish television at 6:00 a.m. on 13 December 1981, General Jaruzelski said:<ref>The original is available at [http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html Konflikty.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112060937/http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html |date=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Today I address myself to you as a soldier and as the head of the Polish government. I address you concerning extraordinarily important questions. Our homeland is at the edge of an abyss. The achievements of many generations and the Polish home that has been built up from the dust are about to turn into ruins. State structures are ceasing to function. Each day delivers new blows to the waning economy./.../<br>The atmosphere of conflicts, misunderstanding, hatred causes moral degradation, surpasses the limits of toleration. Strikes, the readiness to strike, actions of protest have become a norm of life. Even school youth are being drawn into this. Yesterday evening, many public buildings remained seized. The cries are voiced to physical reprisals with the 'reds', with people who have different opinions. <br>The cases of terror, threats and moral vendetta, of even direct violence are on the rise. A wave of impudent crimes, robberies and burglaries is running across the country. The underground business sharks' fortunes, already reaching millions, are growing. Chaos and demoralization have reached the magnitude of a catastrophe. People have reached the limit of psychological toleration. Many people are struck by despair. Not only days, but hours as well are bringing forth the all-national disaster./.../<br>Citizens!<br>The load of responsibility that falls on me on this dramatic moment in the Polish history is huge. It is my duty to take this responsibility - concerning the future of Poland, that my generation fought for on all the fronts of the war and for which they sacrificed the best years of their life. I declare, that today the Military Council of National Salvation has been formed. In accordance with the Constitution, the State Council has imposed martial law all over the country. I wish that everyone understood the motives of our actions. A military coup, military dictatorship is not our goal./.../<br> In longer perspective, none of Poland's problems can be solved with the use of violence. The Military Council of National Salvation does not replace constitutional organs of power. Its only purpose is to keep the legal balance of the country, to create guarantees that give a chance to restore order and discipline. This is the ultimate way to bring the country out of the crisis, to save the country from collapse./.../<br>I appeal to all the citizens. A time of heavy trials has arrived. And we have to stand those in order to prove that we are worthy of Poland.<br>Before all the Polish people and the whole world I would like to repeat the immortal words: <br>\n::'''''[[Poland Is Not Yet Lost|Poland has not yet perished, so long as we still live]]!'''''</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Able Archer 83]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]]\n* [[Pacification of Wujek]]\n* [[Polish 1970 protests]]\n* [[Pozna\u0144 1956 protests]]\n* [[Romanian Revolution]], 1989\n* [[Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981]]\n* [[Telephone tapping in the Eastern Bloc]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leopold Labedz, ''Poland Under Jaruzelski: A Comprehensive Sourcebook on Poland During and After Martial Law''\n* George Sanford, ''Military Rule in Poland: The Rebuilding of Communist Power, 1981\u20131983''\n{{Portal|Poland|History|Communism|War|1980s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Martial law in Poland}}\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB211/index.htm Solidarity and Martial Law in Poland: 25 Years Later], [[National Security Archive]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110112170636/http://www.onwar.com/aced/chrono/c1900s/yr80/fpoland1981.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981-1983]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080105033603/http://www.tenetour.com/history9.php Martial Law in Poland]\n* [http://www.videofact.com/english/stanwoj2.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dKhITm9-5TU Video of Jaruzelski declaring martial law], [[Telewizja Polska|TVP]]/[[YouTube]]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/zyziza/martial_law_in_poland Photo Gallery by zyziza at pbase.com]\n\n{{History of the People's Republic of Poland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martial Law In Poland}}\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1981 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1981 in politics]]\n[[Category:1982 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1982 in politics]]\n[[Category:1983 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1983 in politics]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1983]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws]]\n[[Category:Martial law|Poland]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Poland]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Poland]]\n[[Category:Poland\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Solidarity (Polish trade union)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Martial law in Poland\n| place       = {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Poland]]\n| partof      = the [[Soviet reaction to the Polish crisis of 1980\u20131981]]\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon|Polish People's Republic}} [[Polish People's Republic]]\n* [[Polish People's Army]]\n* [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia (MO)]]\n* [[ZOMO]]\n* [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Service (SB)]]\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|Soviet Union}} ({{small|Intelligence support and military equipment}})\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|}} [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity Movement]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]] <br><small>(from 1982)</small>\n* Protesters\n----\n'''Supported by:''' \n{{flag|United States}} ({{small|Financial support}})\n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = \n*91 killed\n*Thousands arrested\n| commander1  = [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] \n* [[Czes\u0142aw Kiszczak]]\n| commander2  = [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]]\n*[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Frasyniuk]]\n| image       = File:T-55A Martial law Poland.jpg\n| image_size  = 280px\n| caption     = A column of Polish [[T-55]] tanks enters the town of [[Zb\u0105szy\u0144]] while moving east towards the city of [[Pozna\u0144]], 13 December 1981\n| date        = 13 December 1981 \u2013 22 July 1983\n({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=12|day1=13|year1=1981|month2=07|day2=22|year2=1983}})\n| result      = Decisive Polish government victory\n*Crackdown on opposition\n*Protests suppressed \n*Deepened economic crisis\n*Continued resistance until 1989\n| strength1   ='''Initial strength''':<ref>https://culture.pl/en/article/the-day-poland-stood-still-memories-from-the-introduction-of-martial-law</ref>\n*80,000 soldiers\n*30,000 policemen\n*1,750 tanks\n*1,900 combat vehicles\n*9,000 cars\n| strength2   = ~ 10 million (1981)\n}}\n\n'''Martial law in Poland''' ({{lang-pl|Stan wojenny w Polsce}}) refers to the period between 13 December 1981 and 22 July 1983, when the [[authoritarian]] [[communist government]] of the [[Polish People's Republic]] drastically restricted normal life by introducing [[martial law]] and a [[military junta]] in an attempt to throttle political opposition, in particular the [[Solidarity Movement]]. Thousands of opposition activists were [[Internment|imprisoned]] without charge and as many as 91 killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref> Although martial law was lifted in 1983, many of the [[political prisoner]]s were not released until a general [[amnesty]] in 1986.\n\nSince the 1970s, communist Poland was in a deep [[economic recession]]. The First Secretary [[Edward Gierek]] made large incessant loans from western creditors to achieve a better economic output that instead resulted in a domestic crisis. Basic goods were being heavily [[Rationing|rationed]] which acted as a stimuli for the establishment of a first anti-communist [[trade union]] in the [[Eastern Bloc]], known as Solidarity, in 1980. Gierek, who permitted the trade union to appear per the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]], was dismissed from his post less than a month later under pressure from the USSR and confined to [[house arrest]]. Poland's already somewhat liberal policies concerning the opposition were worrisome for hardliners in the [[Soviet Union]], who feared that the Poles may overthrow communism and ally themselves with the [[Western Bloc]]. The Soviets were particularly uneasy as the departure of Eastern Bloc's most populous nation from [[Comecon]] would trigger further financial and economic problems that would bring an end to communist rule in Central-Eastern Europe. After a series of strikes and demonstrations by employees of chief industrial regions, Poland was directly heading towards bankruptcy. \n\nThe [[Military Council of National Salvation]] was formed by the new First Secretary of the Polish United Workers' Party, General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], who was determined to put an end to the demonstrations and crush the opposition by force if necessary. There is speculation whether Jaruzelski instigated martial law to prevent bloodshed if the Soviets and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries were to enter Poland under the mutual assistance treaty, like in the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] and the [[invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968]]. On 13 December 1981, Jaruzelski announced the introduction of martial law in a televised speech addressed to the entire nation. The Polish People's Army, [[Citizen's Militia]] (MO), [[ZOMO]] special units and tanks rolled onto the streets to scare off demonstrators, begin regular patrols and maintain [[curfew]]. Intercity travelling was forbidden unless a permit was granted by the authorities, food shortages intensified and censorship was placed on all media and [[post]]. The [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|secret services (SB)]] [[wiretapped]] phones in public booths and state institutions. \n\nOn 16 December, pro-Solidarity miners organized a strike against the declaration of the martial law at the [[Wujek Coal Mine]] in the industrial city of [[Katowice]]. The ZOMO squads, nicknamed \"Communist [[Gestapo]]\" by the opposition, brutally [[Pacification of Wujek|pacified Wujek]], which resulted in the deaths of 9 miners. All other [[1982 demonstrations in Poland|demonstrations across Poland]] were met with armed force of the services, which utilized [[water cannons]], [[tear gas]], [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]], truncheons and clubs to disperse crowds and beat protesters. Thousands were detained and some were tortured in state prisons. On 31 August 1982, in the copper-mining town of [[Lubin]], 3 people were mortally wounded by ZOMO. Until the end of the martial law on 22 July 1983, approximately 91 people were killed, though this figure varies and is still debated among historians.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6175517.stm Poland marks communist crackdown], [[BBC News]], 13 December 2006</ref>\n\n==Prelude==\n{{main|History of Poland (1945\u20131989)}}\n===Reforms of Edward Gierek (1970-1975)===\n[[File:Photograph of President Gerald R. Ford, First Secretary Edward Gierek of Poland, and Mrs. Stanislawa Gierek Waving from the Blue Room Balcony during a State Arrival Ceremony - NARA - 7462054.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Gierek in the [[White House]] with President [[Gerald Ford]], 1974]]\nWhen [[Edward Gierek]] succeeded [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Gomu\u0142ka|Gomu\u0142ka]] as the head of state in 1970, he took decisive measures to boost economic growth and develop modern infrastructure. Gierek, a more [[Liberalism|liberal]] figure than his predecessor, was determined to make [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]] the wealthiest and most economically significant communist country of the [[Eastern Bloc]]. However, these ideas prompted resistance from hardline communist leadership as the reform would effectively abandon the fundamental principles of a [[Planned economy|centrally planned]] [[Marxism|Marxist]] economy. The grip and emphasis on state-owned enterprises and state-controlled prices or trade was eventually loosened. Small private businesses began to appear and Poland recorded temporary growth in [[GDP]] and an improvement in living conditions. \n\nGierek maintained close ties with the [[United States]], which he subsequently used for diplomatic and economic purposes. In order to continue with the reforms, large sums of money were borrowed from [[creditors]] in the [[Western Bloc]]. These sequential and uninterrupted loans were primarily targeted at establishing heavy industry, mines or manufacturing facilities that would produce goods for [[export]]. The projected income from the exports would then be used to pay off the [[debt]]. Apart from financing the economic sector, the money was spent on [[social housing]] and on expanding road connections, for example the first fully operational [[highway]] linking Warsaw with industrial [[Silesia]] was opened for traffic in 1976. Furthermore, over 1.8 million [[plattenbau]] flats were constructed to house the growing population. Agricultural output rose by 22% between 1971 and 1975. Gierek also initiated the construction of [[Warszawa Centralna]], Europe's most modern railway station at the time.\n\n===Crisis; debt, rationing and shortages (1976-1981)===\n[[File:Kartka cukier 1kg 07-76.jpg|thumb|left|140px|A ration card for sugar, 1976]]\nAs expenditures increased and debts accumulated, the West would no longer grant Poland loans. Moreover, the [[1973 oil crisis|1973]] and [[1979 oil crisis|1979 oil crises]] affected the fragile economy. Due to previous GDP growth, higher income and expanded industries, the demand for certain goods and [[consumption]] surged. New factories and state enterprises required fuel, materials and a workforce to operate production lines. Soon, the country started exporting locally-produced stock designated for the Polish populace, thus resulting in widespread [[shortages]]. Because the remaining assets were directed at production, exports and debt repayment, the state also reduced imports to minimize expenses. \n\nIn 1976, the communist government introduced [[ration cards]] for sugar, meat, processed food and dairy. Confectionery, [[cocoa]], coffee, rice, [[tobacco]] and other goods not produced in Poland were so heavily rationed that they were almost permanently unavailable. The living standards began to sharply decline; the supply of imported goods was kept to a low minimum and the county was forced to export everything it could, including coal necessary for basic heating and power plants. [[Power outage]]s were commonplace. By 1980, the debt accounted to over US$23 billion, then almost half of Poland's [[nominal GDP]].        \n\n[[File:Jimmy Carter and Edward Gierek First Secretary of Poland - NARA - 177308.tif|thumb|right|230px|[[Edward Gierek]] (right) with President [[Jimmy Carter]] (left) during his state visit to Warsaw, 1977. The loans and Solidarity were among the chief topics discussed]]\n\nAt the same time, the newly-founded [[Solidarity movement]] encouraged farmers to refrain from selling agricultural products (wheat, grain, fruit and others) to the state as a sign of protest. The actual lack of goods on the market and in stores was caused by the fact that production stopped due to the strikes organized by Solidarity. In 1980, the national income fell by 6% compared to previous year, and in 1981 by 12%. The number of exports declined by 4.2%. Mismanagement and wastefulness were abundant. \n\nOn 6 September 1980, Gierek was dismissed from his office, expelled from the Polish United Workers' Party (possibly under the pressure from the Soviet Union) and falsely charged with [[corruption]]. A year later, on 10 September 1981, the Soviet authorities informed the Polish government that in connection with the prevailing situation in Poland the USSR would cut oil supply to Poland by 64% and gas by 47%. The import of [[diesel]] from the Soviet Union was terminated immediately. This action was intended to force the Polish communist authorities to suppress the demonstrations and dissolve Solidarity. The situation was already dire and gradually worsened, which only fueled anti-communist sentiment. A [[civil war]] was hanging by a thread.\n\nIn 1981, Poland notified [[Club de Paris]] (a group of Western-European central banks) about its [[insolvency]], which caught the attention of the entire world.<ref>http://www.clubdeparis.org/en/traitements/poland-27-04-1981/en</ref>\n\n==Introduction, restrictions, patrols==\n===Secret preparations and provocation===\n[[File:Wojciech Jaruzelski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|General [[Wojciech Jaruzelski|Jaruzelski]] was determined to suppress any opposition along with the [[Solidarity Movement]]]]\nAfter the short tenure of [[Stanis\u0142aw Kania]], General and Minister of Defence [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]] was chosen as the new First Secretary. Before assuming office, Jaruzelski ordered the Polish General Staff to update plans for a nationwide martial law on 22 October 1980.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> In November 1980, the [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Poland)|Ministry of Internal Affairs]] planned to potentially facilitate around 12,900 members of the opposition in state prisons and places of internment. \n\nOn 5 December 1980, Kania spoke of the preparations relating to martial law at the [[Warsaw Pact|Warsaw Pact Summit]] in [[Moscow]]. He presented his own view of how to weaken Solidarity and insisted that a \"psychological-operational method\" would be most appropriate to prevent violence. This method entailed strong [[propaganda]] against the movement and deploying [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa|Secret Services (SB)]] to go undercover and infiltrate Solidarity headquarters in the hope of creating internal conflicts within the opposition. General Jaruzelski was not fully satisfied with the plan, and, in case of failure, already planned radical actions involving the army. Stanis\u0142aw Kania warned [[Brezhnev]] that an armed intervention from the Soviet side to aid Jaruzelski would be met \"with a violent reaction, or even with a national uprising\" that would shake the politics of the Eastern Bloc.     \n\n[[Zbigniew Brzezinski]], chief security advisor to US President [[Jimmy Carter]], stated that \"if the Soviet Union would undertake an armed intervention in Poland, the US would strike back in a [[riposte]] manner\". According to historian and publicist [[Paul Kengor]], the then US President [[Ronald Reagan]] considered sending American troops to Poland to scare off the Soviets.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> This claim was not supported by Brzezinski nor by [[Richard Pipes]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> Kengor then elaborated that Reagan eventually abandoned the plan after he was convinced by his own advisors that the US army stationed across Europe is less capable and much weaker than the Soviet forces.<ref>https://wyborcza.pl/1,75399,3976852.html</ref> \n\n[[File:WieczorWroclawia20marca1981.jpg|thumb|right|240px|A censored regional newspaper that reported about the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which the [[Milicja Obywatelska|Militia]] abused Solidarity members. The censorship was to prevent the slander of state services]] \n\nIn February 1981, the [[Ministry of National Defence (Poland)|Ministry of National Defence]] and Ministry of the Internal Affairs carried out a training scenario, the purpose of which was to explore how martial law will be introduced. The ministries agreed that martial law should be preceded by appropriate propaganda calling for its support, and the decision itself should be based on a pretext that it would bring peace and stability for the society. It was also highlighted that martial law must occur before the fully mobilized [[Fighting Solidarity]] and its allies organize a [[general strike]] that would paralyze the entire country. By March, the situation escalated after the [[Bydgoszcz events]], in which local Solidarity delegates invited for a [[National Council (Poland)|Regional National Council]] meeting in [[Bydgoszcz]] to discuss potential strikes were beaten and abused by the [[Citizens' Militia]] (MO). The event, which was to feature in newspapers as a [[provocation]], was concealed by [[censors]]. On 27 March, Solidarity organized a warning strike directed at the government, but, on 30 March, [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] met with [[Mieczys\u0142aw Rakowski]] and a compromise was achieved. The general strike was called off and the situation stabilized for a short period.\n\nIn July, the Soviets increased their military presence in the military base at [[Borne Sulinowo]], where the [[Red Army]] stationed per [[Warsaw Pact]] agreement as in all other [[Eastern Bloc]] countries. Without notifying the Polish authorities, the Soviets unexpectedly sent over 600 tanks to Borne Sulinowo. A month later, commander-in-chief of the Warsaw Pact, [[Viktor Kulikov]], requested that Soviet military advisors are to be placed in the Polish General Staff and assigned to nearly all Polish regiments. It is suspected that Kulikov, acting on behalf of the Soviet Union, was tasked with sending undercover [[KGB]] agents to monitor the situation in Poland from the Polish military's perspective. His request, however, was immediately denied by the Polish government.<ref name=\"Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne\">{{cite book |surname=Benjamin Weiser |title=Ryszard Kukli\u0144ski. \u017bycie \u015bci\u015ble tajne |publisher=\u015awiat Ksi\u0105\u017cki |location=Warszawa |year=2005 |isbn = 83-7391-673-3}}</ref> \n\nOver 25,000 posters announcing martial law were secretly printed in the USSR, transported to Poland by airplane and hidden in the large building housing the Ministry of Internal Affairs.<ref>[[Ryszard Terlecki]]: ''Miecz i tarcza komunizmu. Historia aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa w Polsce 1944-1990'', Krak\u00f3w 2007, p. 270\u2013271.</ref> The full extent of the actions undertaken by Jaruzelski to instigate martial law was not known by even some of the highest notables in the Central Committee of the [[Polish United Workers' Party]] or the Polish [[Sejm]].\n\n===13 December 1981=== \nOn 12 December 1981, shortly before [[midnight]], the [[Polish Council of State]] gathered in Warsaw's [[Belweder Palace]] and approved nationwide martial law.\n\nAt precisely 00:00 hours (12:00 a.m.), the [[ZOMO|Motorized Reserves of the Citizens' Militia]] (ZOMO) began the operation and arrested the first members of Solidarity who were at close reach. In total, between 70,000 and 80,000 soldiers of the People's army and 30,000 functionaries of the Ministry of Internal Affairs (including SB, ZOMO and the Militia) were deployed for action. Around 1,750 tanks, 1,400 armoured vehicles, 500 militarized transport units, 9000 cars and several [[helicopter]] [[squadron]]s were in service.<ref>''From Solidarity to Martial Law: The Polish Crisis of 1980\u20131981: A Documentary History'' by Andrzej Paczkowski, Malcolm Byrne. Central European University Press, Budapest 2007. p. xxxiii</ref> 25% of all units concentrated in the capital, Warsaw, or in surrounding localities.       \n\nAfter the introduction of martial law on 13 December 1981, pro-[[democracy]] movements such as [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] and other smaller organisations were banned, and their leaders, including [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]], jailed overnight. In the morning, thousands of soldiers in military vehicles appeared on the streets of every major city. A [[curfew]] was imposed, the national borders sealed, airports closed, and road access to main cities restricted. Telephone lines were disconnected, mail subject to renewed [[postal censorship]], all independent official organizations were criminalized, and classes in schools and universities suspended.\n\nDuring the initial imposition of martial law, several dozen people were killed. Official reports during the crackdown claimed about a dozen fatalities, while a [[Sejm of the Republic of Poland|parliamentary]] commission in the years 1989\u20131991 arrived at a figure of over 90.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html Ofiary stanu wojennego i lat nast\u0119pnych do 1989] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108144638/http://wyborcza.pl/1,77062,3787704.html |date=2014-01-08 }} by Piotr Lipi\u0144ski</ref> In the deadliest incident, nine coal miners were killed by: \"[[ZOMO]]\" paramilitary police during the [[strike-breaking]] at the [[Pacification of Wujek]] on 16 December 1981. Others were also killed and wounded during a massive second wave of demonstrations on [[August 31, 1982 demonstrations in Poland|31 August 1982]].\n\n[[File:Telegr.jpg|thumb|right|A censored telegram, 1982]]\n\nThe government imposed a six-day work week while the mass media, public services, healthcare services, power stations, coal mines, sea ports, railway stations, and most key factories were placed under military management, with employees having to follow military orders or face a [[court martial]]. As part of the crackdown, media and educational institutions underwent \"verification\", a process that tested each employee's attitude towards the regime and to the Solidarity movement; as a result, thousands of journalists, teachers and professors were banned from their professions. [[Military court]]s were established to bypass the normal court system, to imprison those spreading \"false information\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/special_report/1999/09/99/iron_curtain/timelines/poland_81.stm 1981: Martial law], [[BBC]]</ref> In an attempt to crush resistance, civilian phone lines were routinely tapped and monitored by government agents.\n\nAt the invitation of Jaruzelski, a delegation of the ruling [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party]] visited Poland between 27 and 29 December. The Hungarians shared with their Polish colleagues their experiences on crushing the [[1956 Hungarian revolution|\"counterrevolution\" of 1956]]. Earlier in the autumn of 1981, Polish television had broadcast a special film on the 1956 events in Hungary, showing scenes of rebels hanging security officers etc.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wI9TUaZZeAMC&pg=PA499&dq=jaruzelski+1981+martial+law#v=onepage&q=jaruzelski%201981%20martial%20law&f=false Google Books]</ref>\n\nThe introduction of martial law was enthusiastically supported by some figures on the right like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]],<ref>Polish Western affairs, Volumes 31\u201332. Instytut Zachodni, 1990. [https://books.google.com/books?id=PepBAAAAYAAJ&q=%22jedrzej+giertych%22&dq=%22jedrzej+giertych%22&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CEsQ6AEwCThk p. 165]</ref> who believed Solidarity to be a disguised communist movement dominated by Jewish [[Trotskyite]]s.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:AGAD_Gen._Wojciech_jaruzelski_13_grudnia_1981.png|Jaruzelski in a TV studio announcing the introduction of martial law\nFile:Stan wojenny obwieszczenie.jpg|The proclamation of martial law by the State Council\nFile:Stan wojenny w Polsce - 1981-1983 - 12a.JPG|Members of the [[Milicja_Obywatelska|Citizens' Militia]] race to disperse crowds of protesters\n</gallery>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Kartka P3 11-83.jpeg|thumb|Food, alcohol, and cigarettes [[rationing]] card]]\n\nEven after martial law was lifted, a number of restrictions remained in place for several years that drastically reduced the [[civil liberties]] of the citizenry. It also led to severe economic consequences. The ruling [[military dictatorship]] instituted major price rises (dubbed \"economic reforms\"), which resulted in a fall in real wages of 20% or more. The resulting [[economic crisis]] led to the [[rationing]] of most products and materials, including basic foodstuffs.\n\nAs a consequence of economic hardship and political repression, an exodus of Poles saw 700,000 emigrate to the West between 1981 and 1989.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nypuJ8BARiMC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=poland+economy+1980s&source=bl&ots=iR_fCDeyE6&sig=q2hNTHlJPvd7MOfHIhY-lEKmJsc&hl=en&ei=lLEbS6OKG8z_4Abzt4TnAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=poland%20economy%201980s&f=false Google Books]</ref> \nA number of international flights were even hijacked in attempts to flee the country and its economic problems. Between December 1980 and October 1983, 11 Polish flights were hijacked to [[Berlin Tempelhof Airport]] alone.<ref>[http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 A Symbol Of Allied Solidarity Will Disappear. Berlin - The Atlantic Times] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707184128/http://www.atlantic-times.com/archive_detail.php?recordID=673 |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref>\n\nAround the same time, a group calling themselves the \"Polish Revolutionary Home Army\" seized the Polish Embassy in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]] on 6 September 1982, taking several diplomats as hostages. However this turned out to be an apparent provocation by the communist Polish secret services aiming to discredit the Solidarity movement.<ref>[http://www.start.umd.edu/start/data/tops/terrorist_organization_profile.asp?id=4206 Terrorist Organization Profile: Polish Revolutionary Home Army]</ref>\n\n==International response==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2009}}\n\nAfter the \"Wujek\" Coal Mine incident in Katowice on 23 December 1981, the [[United States]] imposed [[economic sanctions]] against the [[People's Republic of Poland]]. In 1982 the United States suspended [[most favored nation]] trade status until 1987 and vetoed Poland's application for membership in the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>[http://countrystudies.us/poland/92.htm Poland - The United States]</ref>\n\nPope John Paul II wrote a [https://www.nytimes.com/1981/03/29/world/pope-calls-for-justice-and-peace-in-polish-quest-for-a-settlement.html letter] to the Primate of Poland, Stefan Cardinal Wyszynski, in which he called for peace talks between the state and the workers, supporting the Poles' \"undeniable right to resolve their problems by themselves.\"\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Ruling of unconstitutionality===\nAfter the [[fall of Communism in Poland]] in 1989, members of a parliamentary commission determined that martial law had been imposed in clear violation of the country's [[constitution]] which had authorized the executive to declare martial law only between parliamentary sessions (at other times the decision was to be taken by the [[Sejm]]). However, the Sejm had been in session at the time when martial law was instituted. In 1992 the Sejm declared the 1981 imposition of martial law to be unlawful and unconstitutional.\n\n===Soviet intervention debate===\n{{further|Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981}}\n\nThe instigators of the martial law, such as [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], argue that the army crackdown rescued Poland from a possibly disastrous [[military intervention]] of the [[Soviet Union]], [[East Germany]], and other [[Warsaw Pact]] countries (similar to the earlier interventions in [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungary in 1956]] and [[Prague Spring|Czechoslovakia in 1968]]).<ref>[http://www.euronews.net/2008/10/02/jaruzelski-says-martial-law-saved-poland/ Jaruzelski says martial law saved Poland], [[Euronews]], 02/10/08</ref> Public figures who supported the introduction of martial law (including some of the right-wing figures like [[J\u0119drzej Giertych]]) would also refer to that threat.\n\nIn 2009, archive documents hinted that in a conversation Jaruzelski had with [[Viktor Kulikov]], a Soviet military leader, Jaruzelski himself begged for Soviet intervention as his domestic control was deteriorating.<ref>[http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php Newpolandexpress.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009161848/http://www.newpolandexpress.pl/npe_news_story-1531-jaruzelski_invited_soviet_invasion.php |date=2011-10-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rferl.org/content/Interview_Polands_Jaruzelski_Again_Denies_Seeking_Soviet_Intervention_Against_Solidarity/1902431.html Rferl.org]</ref> Jaruzelski responded by claiming the document was 'just another falsification'.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Declaration script==\nLed by [[General of the Army]] [[Wojciech Jaruzelski]], the [[Military Council of National Salvation]] (''Wojskowa Rada Ocalenia Narodowego'', WRON) usurped for itself powers reserved for wartime, hence the name. The plan was presented to the government of the [[Soviet Union]] before the declaration in March 1981.\n\nAppearing on Polish television at 6:00 a.m. on 13 December 1981, General Jaruzelski said:<ref>The original is available at [http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html Konflikty.pl] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112060937/http://www.konflikty.pl/a,395,Czasy_najnowsze,Przemowienie_gen._Jaruzelskiego.html |date=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Today I address myself to you as a soldier and as the head of the Polish government. I address you concerning extraordinarily important questions. Our homeland is at the edge of an abyss. The achievements of many generations and the Polish home that has been built up from the dust are about to turn into ruins. State structures are ceasing to function. Each day delivers new blows to the waning economy./.../<br>The atmosphere of conflicts, misunderstanding, hatred causes moral degradation, surpasses the limits of toleration. Strikes, the readiness to strike, actions of protest have become a norm of life. Even school youth are being drawn into this. Yesterday evening, many public buildings remained seized. The cries are voiced to physical reprisals with the 'reds', with people who have different opinions. <br>The cases of terror, threats and moral vendetta, of even direct violence are on the rise. A wave of impudent crimes, robberies and burglaries is running across the country. The underground business sharks' fortunes, already reaching millions, are growing. Chaos and demoralization have reached the magnitude of a catastrophe. People have reached the limit of psychological toleration. Many people are struck by despair. Not only days, but hours as well are bringing forth the all-national disaster./.../<br>Citizens!<br>The load of responsibility that falls on me on this dramatic moment in the Polish history is huge. It is my duty to take this responsibility - concerning the future of Poland, that my generation fought for on all the fronts of the war and for which they sacrificed the best years of their life. I declare, that today the Military Council of National Salvation has been formed. In accordance with the Constitution, the State Council has imposed martial law all over the country. I wish that everyone understood the motives of our actions. A military coup, military dictatorship is not our goal./.../<br> In longer perspective, none of Poland's problems can be solved with the use of violence. The Military Council of National Salvation does not replace constitutional organs of power. Its only purpose is to keep the legal balance of the country, to create guarantees that give a chance to restore order and discipline. This is the ultimate way to bring the country out of the crisis, to save the country from collapse./.../<br>I appeal to all the citizens. A time of heavy trials has arrived. And we have to stand those in order to prove that we are worthy of Poland.<br>Before all the Polish people and the whole world I would like to repeat the immortal words: <br>\n::'''''[[Poland Is Not Yet Lost|Poland has not yet perished, so long as we still live]]!'''''</blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Able Archer 83]]\n* [[Fighting Solidarity]]\n* [[Pacification of Wujek]]\n* [[Polish 1970 protests]]\n* [[Pozna\u0144 1956 protests]]\n* [[Romanian Revolution]], 1989\n* [[Soviet reaction to the Polish Crisis of 1980-1981]]\n* [[Telephone tapping in the Eastern Bloc]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Leopold Labedz, ''Poland Under Jaruzelski: A Comprehensive Sourcebook on Poland During and After Martial Law''\n* George Sanford, ''Military Rule in Poland: The Rebuilding of Communist Power, 1981\u20131983''\n{{Portal|Poland|History|Communism|War|1980s}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Martial law in Poland}}\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB211/index.htm Solidarity and Martial Law in Poland: 25 Years Later], [[National Security Archive]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110112170636/http://www.onwar.com/aced/chrono/c1900s/yr80/fpoland1981.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981-1983]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080105033603/http://www.tenetour.com/history9.php Martial Law in Poland]\n* [http://www.videofact.com/english/stanwoj2.htm Martial Law in Poland 1981]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dKhITm9-5TU Video of Jaruzelski declaring martial law], [[Telewizja Polska|TVP]]/[[YouTube]]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/zyziza/martial_law_in_poland Photo Gallery by zyziza at pbase.com]\n\n{{History of the People's Republic of Poland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martial Law In Poland}}\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:1981 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1981 in politics]]\n[[Category:1982 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1982 in politics]]\n[[Category:1983 in Poland]]\n[[Category:1983 in politics]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Communism in Poland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1981]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1982]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1983]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws]]\n[[Category:Martial law|Poland]]\n[[Category:Military coups in Poland]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Poland]]\n[[Category:Poland\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Solidarity (Polish trade union)]]\n", "name_user": "Oliszydlowski", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e13 December 1981", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martial_law_in_Poland"}
{"title_page": "Spectrum (Say My Name)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 song by Florence and the Machine}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Spectrum (Say My Name)\n| cover      = Florence and the Machine - Spectrum.png\n| alt        = Single cover\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Florence and the Machine]]\n| album      = [[Ceremonials]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|7|6|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[12-inch single|12\"]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Baroque pop]]|[[art pop]]|[[indie pop]] <small> (album version)</small><br />\n|[[orchestral pop]]|[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[krautrock]]|[[disco]] <small>(single version)</small>}}\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|{{Duration|m=5|s=11}} {{small|(album version)}}|{{Duration|m=3|s=38}} {{small|(remix version)}}}}\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Florence Welch]]|[[Paul Epworth]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Paul Epworth|[[Calvin Harris]] {{small|(remix)}}}}\n| prev_title = [[Breath of Life (Florence and the Machine song)|Breath of Life]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Lover to Lover]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|id=iC-_lVzdiFE|title=\"Spectrum\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Spectrum'''\" is a song by English [[indie rock]] band [[Florence and the Machine]] from their second studio album ''[[Ceremonials]]'' (2011). It was written by lead singer [[Florence Welch]] and [[Paul Epworth]] with production being handled by Epworth. The band premiered the song during a concert at Brooklyn's Creators Project on 15 October 2011, prior to the release of the album. The album version of \"Spectrum\" is a downtempo [[orchestral pop]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[krautrock]] and [[disco]] song. The accompanying [[music video]] for the song premiered on 30 May 2012. It was directed by [[David LaChapelle]] and [[Johnny Byrne (choreographer)|John Byrne]].\n\nA remix of the album version of \"Spectrum\", titled \"'''Spectrum (Say My Name)'''\", was released on 6 July 2012 by Island Records, serving as the fourth single from Ceremonials. Scottish DJ [[Calvin Harris]] remixed \"Spectrum\", producing the uptempo single. \"Spectrum (Say My Name)\" became the group's first single to peak at number one on the UK Singles Chart, selling 64,816 copies in its first week. It also reached number one in Ireland and Scotland and has peaked within the top five in Australia and New Zealand.\n\n==Background and composition==\nFlorence and the Machine premiered \"Spectrum\" along with two other songs from the album, \"[[Never Let Me Go (Florence and the Machine song)|Never Let Me Go]]\" and \"Heartlines\", as part of their [[set list]] at [[Brooklyn]]'s Creators Project on 15 October 2011, two weeks before the release of the album.<ref>Sources talking about the premiere of \"Spectrum\", \"Never Let Me Go\" and \"Heartlines\" on 15 October 2011 during the band's [[set list]] at New York's Creators Project before the release of ''Ceremonials'':\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/florence-and-the-machine/59836|title=Watch Florence And The Machine perform three new tracks from 'Ceremonials' - video|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=16 October 2011|accessdate=2 July 2012}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a345974/florence--the-machine-perform-three-new-tracks-live-video.html|title=Florence + the Machine perform three new tracks live - video|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. [[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]]|first=Robert|last=Copsey|date=17 October 2011|accessdate=2 July 2012}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/10/watch-florence-the-machine-debut-3-new-songs-at-cr.html|title=Watch Florence and the Machine Debut Three New Songs at Creator's Project|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|publisher=[[Wolfgang's Vault]]|first=K.|last=Alexander Smith|date=17 October 2011|accessdate=2 July 2012}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/18/showbiz/creators-project-art-music-tech/|title=Creators Project brings together art, music and tech|publisher=[[CNN]]|first=Abbey|last=Goodman|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=2 July 2012}}\n</ref> Musically, \"Spectrum\" is a downtempo [[orchestral pop]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/archive/florence-and-the-machine-ceremonials |title=Florence & The Machine - Ceremonials |publisher=DIY magazine |accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> [[contemporary R&B|R&B]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/florence-and-the-machine/12419 |title=Album review: Florence + The Machine - 'Ceremonials' |publisher=NME |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> [[krautrock]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-florence-the-machine-ceremonials-island-2376712.html |title=Album: Florence + the Machine, Ceremonials (Island) |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> and [[disco]] song with [[Drum kit|drums]] while backing vocals repeatedly sing \"Say my name\" throughout the choruses. According to the sheet music published by [[Universal Music Publishing Group]] on the website Musicnotes.com, the song is set in the key [[B minor]].<ref name=\"musicnotes\">{{cite web|title=Spectrum - Sheet Music (Digital Download)|first1=Florence|last1=Welch|first2=Paul|last2=Epworth|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Universal Music Publishing Group]]}}</ref> The song's beat is set in [[Time signature|common time]], and moves at a [[tempo]] of 124 beats per minute.<ref name=\"musicnotes\"/> Welch's vocals span from the note of F#3 to the note of F#5 or B5 in the [[Calvin Harris]] remix.<ref name=\"musicnotes\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Spectrum\" received mostly positive reviews by critics. While reviewing ''Ceremonials'', Jillian Mapes of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' complimented Welch's vocal performance, stating, \"'Say my name,' she howls then later croons, both filled with sensuality. Welch's impressive vocal range and volume are firing on all cylinders here.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Mapes |first=Jillian |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/465357/florence-the-machine-ceremonials-track-by-track-review |title=Florence + The Machine, 'Ceremonials': Track-By-Track Review |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=2 November 2011 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> A writer of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' praised the song calling it \"a huge, churchy tune, even in the context of the band's typically bombastic blend of [[arena rock]] and [[gospel music|gospel]].\"<ref name=\"rollstone\"/> Lewis Corner from [[Digital Spy]] gave the song four stars out of five, saying \"if there's one thing latest single 'Spectrum' proves, it's that she knows how to write a distinctive uptempo number without compromising her style.\"<ref name=\"digitalspy\"/> He added that the song \"[...] belts over a rapturous chorus complete with rousing piano and delicate strings - demonstrating that techno synths are not the only key to a euphoric hook.\"<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a391975/florence--the-machine-spectrum-single-review.html|title=Florence + the Machine: \"Spectrum\" - Single review - Music Singles Review|first=Lewis|last=Corner|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. [[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]]|date= 6 July 2012|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nMatthew Cole from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' said along with \"Lover to Lover\" and \"Remain Nameless\"; \"spectacular when taken alone or on a playlist.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/florence-and-the-machine-ceremonials/2666|title=Florence and the Machine - Ceremonials|magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|first=Matthew|last=Cole|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Kitty Empire from ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it a mixed remark, saying \"Clubby and kaleidoscopic, 'Spectrum' sounds like another rallying cry.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/oct/30/florence-machine-ceremonials-review |title=Florence and the Machine: Ceremonials \u2013 review|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|first=Kitty|last=Empire|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Margaret Wappler of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said they could hear a \"harp gorgeously flutter[s] and dips around her.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/10/album-review-florence-the-machines-ceremonials.html|title=Album review: Florence + the Machine's 'Ceremonials'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=31 October 2011|first=Margaret|last=Wappler|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> Chris Saunders from [[musicOMH]] compared it, musically, to the song from Florence's previous record ''[[Lungs (album)|Lungs]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/florence-and-the-machine-2_1011.htm|title=Florence And The Machine - Ceremonials (Island)|publisher=[[musicOMH]]|first=Chris|last=Saunders|date=31 October 2011|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' commented; \"The only time she and The Machine stray from the formula is the Krautrock-disco motorik of 'Spectrum'; elsewhere, declamatory piano chords and burring organ underpin the banked [...]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-florence--the-machine-ceremonials-island-2376712.html|title=Album: Florence + the Machine, Ceremonials (Island )|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|first=Andy|last=Gill|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n\n===Background===\nAn accompanying music video for the song was released on Florence and the Machine's [[YouTube]] account on 30 May 2012. Directed by [[David LaChapelle]] and [[Johnny Byrne (choreographer)|John Byrne]], the video depicts ballet dancers of California's Southland Ballet Academy/Festival Ballet Theatre pirouetting, jumping, and dancing around Welch. During an interview, Welch spoke about her collaboration with LaChapelle, \"It was a complete dream to work with David LaChapelle. I collected his books as a teenager, and I fantasised that he would direct the video for 'Spectrum' from the moment the song was written. I still can't believe it actually happened, and I'm completely overjoyed that he felt such a connection with the song.\"<ref name=\"clash\">{{cite web |last=Murray |first=Robin |url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/watch-florence-the-machine-spectrum |title=Watch: Florence & The Machine \u2013 Spectrum |work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=2 July 2012}}</ref> During an interview, LaChapelle also spoke about his collaboration with Welch, \"It's a beautiful song that really touched me and inspired me to create imagery that matches its power. 'Spectrum' is free of scepticism, irony, and the coldness one finds in a lot of contemporary popular music. It's the opposite\u2014full of light, positivity and authentic joy. I hope that I can do justice to this moving modern classic.\"<ref name=\"clash\"/>\n\nAs no official video for the Calvin Harris remix was made, an edit of the original video by a YouTube user known as \"ElsuperTai\" became the official video for that remix.\n\n===Reception===\nUpon the release of the video, critics praised Welch's look and the video's dark atmosphere. A writer of ''Rolling Stone'' wrote, \"Music video legend David LaChappelle rose to the challenge of making a clip for the song, matching its drama and energy with a vivid color pallette and incredibly theatrical staging.\"<ref name=\"rollstone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/florence-and-the-machines-ultra-theatrical-spectrum-clip-20120530 |title=Florence and the Machine's Ultra-Theatrical 'Spectrum (Say My Name)' Clip |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Robbie Daw of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] stated the video's visual is \"as bombastic and over the top as the song itself [...] there's enough completely koo koo eye candy being hurled at us that we're barely even paying attention to the song itself.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Daw |first=Robbie |url=http://idolator.com/6547762/florence-the-machine-spectrum-video |title=Florence + The Machine's \"Spectrum (Say My Name)\" Video: Watch |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]] |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nThe band performed the song on [[The X Factor (U.S. season 1)#Week 8: Semi-final (December 14/15)|first series]] of the [[The X Factor (U.S.)|American version of ''The X Factor'']] during its semi-finals.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=563IavLCjAA</ref> Florence and the Machine added the song to the [[set list]] of their second worldwide [[Ceremonials Tour]] (2011\u201312) where the song was performed during the encore of the concerts along with \"[[No Light, No Light]]\".{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} On 12 September 2012, Florence performed a stripped-down version of the song on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/blogs/2012/09/florence-the-machine-perform-spectrum-say-my-name/ |title=Florence + The Machine Perform \"Spectrum (Say My Name)\" |publisher=NBCUniversal Media|accessdate=13 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Calvin Harris remix==\nA remix of the album version of \"Spectrum\", titled \"'''Spectrum (Say My Name)'''\", was released on 6 July 2012 by [[Island Records]], serving as the fourth single from ''Ceremonials''. Scottish DJ [[Calvin Harris]] remixed \"Spectrum\", producing the uptempo [[electro house]]-inspired single.<ref name=\"digitalspy\" /> \"Spectrum (Say My Name)\" received positive reviews from music critics, praising the production and Welch's vocals.<ref name=\"digitalspy\" /> Commercially, it became the group's first single to peak at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]], selling 64,816 copies in its first week. It also reached number one in Ireland and Scotland and has peaked within the top five in Australia and New Zealand.\n\n===Background and development===\nOn 25 May 2012, a lyric video was released for the [[Calvin Harris]] remix. The song was released as the album's fifth single on 5 July 2012.<ref name=\"itunes\"/> It was serviced to radio in the UK on 2 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radio1.gr/music/forthcoming_uk_singles.htm |title=New Releases U.K. \u2013 Forthcoming Singles |publisher=Radio1 Rodos Greece |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67bCUOYln |archivedate=12 May 2012 |accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref> On the release of the single, the Calvin Harris remix was released. Lewis Corner of Digital Spy commented that \"While the single version is near perfection, an accompanying Calvin Harris remix highlights just how big a Florence house anthem can be\".<ref name=\"digitalspy\" /> The instrumental version of \"Spectrum\" was used extensively during the [[BBC]]'s coverage of the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012 Olympic Games]], often as the backing track to their round-up of the day's sporting action.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n===Commercial performance===\n\"Spectrum\" debuted at number 104 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] based on the sales of the album version.<ref>{{cite web |last=Williams |first=Paul |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1050348 |title=Midweek Charts: Florence eyeing first singles chart-topper |work=[[Music Week]] |publisher=Intent Media |date=11 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> On 15 July 2012, following the release of the Calvin Harris remix of the song, it climbed the chart to become the band's first number-one single in the UK, selling 64,816 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1050399 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Newton Faulkner needs just 16k sales to hit No.1 |work=Music Week |publisher=Intent Media |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=16 July 2012}}</ref> The song stayed on top of the chart for three weeks. It also debuted at number 35 on the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]], until rising to number two, becoming the group's first top ten single in that country. It peaked at the top spot in the Republic of Ireland. In the UK, it was the best-selling single of the third quarter of 2012, selling 453,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-biggest-selling-singles-of-the-summer-revealed-1626/|title=The biggest selling singles of the summer revealed! |date=4 October 2012 |accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> The song has sold 554,000 copies in the UK in 2012, and was the 19th best-selling single of 2012.<ref name=\"chartuk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles-of-2012-revealed-1784/ |title=The Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles Of 2012 revealed! |author=Dan Lane |publisher=Official Charts Company |date=2 January 2013|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> However, in 2013, it was certified platinum for selling over 600,000 copies. It is Florence + the Machine's best-selling single in the United Kingdom.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| headline  = \"Spectrum (Say My Name)\" Remixes [[Extended play|EP]]<ref name=\"itunes\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/spectrum-say-my-name-remixes/id531158564 |title=Spectrum (Say My Name) <nowiki>[Remixes]</nowiki> \u2013 EP by Florence + The Machine |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (UK). [[Apple Inc.|Apple Inc]] |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n| title1    = Spectrum (Say My Name)\n| note1     = [[Calvin Harris]] Remix\n| length1   = 3:38\n| title2    = Spectrum (Say My Name)\n| note2     = [[AlunaGeorge]] Remix\n| length2   = 3:29\n| title3    = Spectrum (Say My Name)\n| note3     = [[Maya Jane Coles]] Remix\n| length3   = 5:00\n| title4    = Spectrum (Say My Name)\n| note4     = Taito Tikaro and Flavio Zarza Remix\n| length4   = 7:26\n}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2012-13)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|4|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|accessdate=23 July 2012}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"{{singlechart|Austria|51|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|2|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 July 2012}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|9|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 August 2012}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|28|year=2012|week=44|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|13|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 August 2012}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|32|artist=Florence + The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|songid=914101|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 March 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungarydance|27|artist=Florence and the Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|year=2012|week=49|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 December 2012}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungary|1|artist=Florence and the Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|year=2012|week=40|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|artist=Florence and the Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|accessdate=27 January 2020}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Israelairplay|4|artist=Florence and The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|year=2012|week=34|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|55|artist=Florence and The Machine|song=Spectrum (Say My Name)|rowheader=true|acces