{"title_page": "John Flittie", "text_new": "'''John Flittie''' (March 22, 1856 \u2013 January 21, 1913) was a U.S. politician who served as [[North Dakota]]'s first [[North Dakota Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] from 1889 to 1892.<ref>[http://www.nd.gov/sos/about/history.html North Dakota Secretary of State | About the Secretary of State<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nJohan Flittie was born in [[Lesja]], in [[Oppland]], [[Norway]]. He was the son of Johannes Throndson Flittie and  Anna Johannesdotter Flittie.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50\n|title=Flitti,  Lesja herad, Oppland\n|publisher= Matrikkelutkastet av 1950\n|author=     \n|date=  \n|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\nHis family emigrated to [[North America]] in 1867, settling in [[Watonwan County]], [[Minnesota]].<ref>Arnfinn Kjelland, ''Bygdebok for Lesja - Bind 2 - 1992'', s.521. Website: {{cite web|url=http://www2.hivolda.no/ahf/historie/lesja/bygdebok.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618164141/http://www2.hivolda.no/ahf/historie/lesja/bygdebok.htm |archivedate=2007-06-18 }}.</ref> He graduated from Mankato Normal School (now [[Minnesota State University, Mankato]]) in 1878 and moved to [[Dakota Territory]] soon after.<ref>Castle, Henry A., ''Minnesota: Its Story and Biography. Vol. I-III''. Chicago and New York, USA: Lewis Publishing, 1915. Vol. III, p. 1605.</ref> He was a member of the Dakota Territorial Council (the [[upper house]] of the territorial [[legislature]]) in 1885\u20131886, and won election as a [[North Dakota Republican Party|Republican]] to the newly created office of Secretary of State in 1889. After serving an abbreviated 1-year term, he was re-elected to a full 2-year term in 1890. He did not seek re-election in 1892. He died in [[Williston, North Dakota]].<ref>North Dakota Blue Book, 2005</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n before=none|\n title=[[List of Secretaries of State of North Dakota|Secretary of State of North Dakota]]|\n years=1889&ndash;1892|\n after=[[Christian M. Dahl]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NDSOS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flittie, John}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:Minnesota State University, Mankato alumni]]\n[[Category:Norwegian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Watonwan County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dakota Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Williston, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''John Flittie''' (March 22, 1856 \u2013 January 21, 1913) was a U.S. politician who served as [[North Dakota]]'s first [[North Dakota Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] from 1889 to 1892.<ref>[http://www.nd.gov/sos/about/history.html North Dakota Secretary of State | About the Secretary of State<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nJohan Flittie was born in [[Lesja]], in [[Oppland]], [[Norway]]. He was the son of Johannes Throndson Flittie and  Anna Johannesdotter Flittie.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50\n|title=Flitti,  Lesja herad, Oppland\n|publisher= Matrikkelutkastet av 1950\n|author=     \n|date=  \n|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\nHis family emigrated to [[North America]] in 1867, settling in [[Watonwan County]], [[Minnesota]].<ref>Arnfinn Kjelland, ''Bygdebok for Lesja - Bind 2 - 1992'', s.521. Website: {{cite web|url=http://www2.hivolda.no/ahf/historie/lesja/bygdebok.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618164141/http://www2.hivolda.no/ahf/historie/lesja/bygdebok.htm |archivedate=2007-06-18 }}.</ref> He graduated from Mankato Normal School (now [[Minnesota State University, Mankato]]) in 1878 and moved to [[Dakota Territory]] soon after.<ref>Castle, Henry A., ''Minnesota: Its Story and Biography. Vol. I-III''. Chicago and New York, USA: Lewis Publishing, 1915. Vol. III, p. 1605.</ref> He was a member of the Dakota Territorial Council (the [[upper house]] of the territorial [[legislature]]) in 1885-1886, and won election as a [[North Dakota Republican Party|Republican]] to the newly created office of Secretary of State in 1889. After serving an abbreviated 1-year term, he was re-elected to a full 2-year term in 1890. He did not seek re-election in 1892. He died in [[Williston, North Dakota]].<ref>North Dakota Blue Book, 2005</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n before=none|\n title=[[List of Secretaries of State of North Dakota|Secretary of State of North Dakota]]|\n years=1889&ndash;1892|\n after=[[Christian M. Dahl]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NDSOS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flittie, John}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:Minnesota State University, Mankato alumni]]\n[[Category:Norwegian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Watonwan County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dakota Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Williston, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1885-1886 \u2192 1885\u20131886", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Flittie"}
{"title_page": "LeRoy Erickson", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Senator\n| name =  LeRoy Erickson\n| image=\n| image_size=160px\n| caption =\n| state = North Dakota\n| state_house =North Dakota\n| district = 26th\n| term_start =1967\n| term_end = 1968\n| predecessor = \n| successor =\n| constituency =\n| state2 = \n| state_house2 =\n| district2 =\n| term_start2 =1973\n| term_end2=1980\n| office3=Member of the [[North Dakota Senate]]\n| term3=1981\u20131984\n| majority = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1926|5|15}}\n| birth_place =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1997|1|14|1926|5|15}}\n| death_place =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| profession =farmer\n| residence =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| relations=\n| alma_mater=\n| spouse =\n| religion = \n| children=\n| website =\n|branch=\n|serviceyears=\n|rank=\n|battles=\n|allegiance=\n}}\n'''Kenneth LeRoy Erickson''' (May 15, 1926 \u2013 January 14, 1997)  was an American farmer and politician who was a member of the [[North Dakota House of Representatives]] and [[North Dakota Senate]].  He was a delegate to the 1971-1972 North Dakota Constitutional Convention.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/conscon1971.html|title= Constitutional Convention, 1971-1972|publisher= State Historical Society of North Dakota   \n|accessdate= May 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nErickson was born near [[De Lamere, North Dakota]]. He was the son of Edward Selmer Erickson (1894-1965) and Agnes Martinson Erickson (1896-1967). In 1944, his parents retired and he began farming his family farm in rural [[Sargent County, North Dakota|Sargent County]]. He also served on the Council of Immanuel Lutheran Church in DeLamere and as a Township Supervisor for Hall Township in Sargent County.<ref name=\"und\">{{cite web|url=http://apps.library.und.edu/archon/index.php?p=collections/findingaid&id=568&q=&rootcontentid=72144|title=LeRoy Erickson Papers|publisher=webapp.und.edu|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=  http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/conscon1971.html\n|title= Erickson, Hans O.|publisher= Sargent County (ND) Teller |date= September 9, 1926 |accessdate= May 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe represented District 26 in the North Dakota House from 1967-1968 and 1973-1980 and in the Senate from 1981\u20131984.<ref name=\"digitalhorizonsonline\">{{cite web|url=http://digitalhorizonsonline.org/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/uw-ndshs&CISOPTR=10058&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|title=Digital Horizons : Item Viewer|publisher=digitalhorizonsonline.org|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref><ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=North Dakota Blue Book|author=North Dakota. Dept. of State|date=1981|publisher=Daily Tribune|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CICHAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erickson, LeRoy}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sargent County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:North Dakota state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the North Dakota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:American Lutherans]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Senator\n| name =  LeRoy Erickson\n| image=\n| image_size=160px\n| caption =\n| state = North Dakota\n| state_house =North Dakota\n| district = 26th\n| term_start =1967\n| term_end = 1968\n| predecessor = \n| successor =\n| constituency =\n| state2 = \n| state_house2 =\n| district2 =\n| term_start2 =1973\n| term_end2=1980\n| office3=Member of the [[North Dakota Senate]]\n| term3=1981\u20131984\n| majority = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1926|5|15}}\n| birth_place =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1997|1|14|1926|5|15}}\n| death_place =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| profession =farmer\n| residence =DeLamere, North Dakota\n| relations=\n| alma_mater=\n| spouse =\n| religion = \n| children=\n| website =\n|branch=\n|serviceyears=\n|rank=\n|battles=\n|allegiance=\n}}\n'''Kenneth LeRoy Erickson''' (May 15, 1926 \u2013 January 14, 1997)  was an American farmer and politician who was a member of the [[North Dakota House of Representatives]] and [[North Dakota Senate]].  He was a delegate to the 1971-1972 North Dakota Constitutional Convention.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/conscon1971.html|title= Constitutional Convention, 1971-1972|publisher= State Historical Society of North Dakota   \n|accessdate= May 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nErickson was born near [[De Lamere, North Dakota]]. He was the son of Edward Selmer Erickson (1894-1965) and Agnes Martinson Erickson (1896-1967). In 1944, his parents retired and he began farming his family farm in rural [[Sargent County, North Dakota|Sargent County]]. He also served on the Council of Immanuel Lutheran Church in DeLamere and as a Township Supervisor for Hall Township in Sargent County.<ref name=\"und\">{{cite web|url=http://apps.library.und.edu/archon/index.php?p=collections/findingaid&id=568&q=&rootcontentid=72144|title=LeRoy Erickson Papers|publisher=webapp.und.edu|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=  http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/conscon1971.html\n|title= Erickson, Hans O.|publisher= Sargent County (ND) Teller |date= September 9, 1926 |accessdate= May 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe represented District 26 in the North Dakota House from 1967-1968 and 1973-1980 and in the Senate from 1981-1984.<ref name=\"digitalhorizonsonline\">{{cite web|url=http://digitalhorizonsonline.org/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/uw-ndshs&CISOPTR=10058&CISOBOX=1&REC=1|title=Digital Horizons : Item Viewer|publisher=digitalhorizonsonline.org|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref><ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=North Dakota Blue Book|author=North Dakota. Dept. of State|date=1981|publisher=Daily Tribune|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CICHAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erickson, LeRoy}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sargent County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:North Dakota state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the North Dakota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:North Dakota Republicans]]\n[[Category:American Lutherans]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n\n\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1981-1984 \u2192 1981\u20131984", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LeRoy_Erickson"}
{"title_page": "George H. Dickey", "text_new": "{{Other uses|George Dickey (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''George H. Dickey''' (1858&ndash;1923) was an [[United States|American]] lawyer from [[Valley City, North Dakota]]. He served in the Territorial House of Representatives of the [[Dakota Territory]] Legislative Assembly in 1881\u20131882.<ref>[http://legis.state.sd.us/historical/LegislatorDetail.aspx?MemberID=3245 South Dakota Legislature-Historical Detail-Legislator Information-George Dickey]</ref> [[Dickey County, North Dakota]] is named in his honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nd.gov/content.htm?parentCatID=83&id=County%20History |title=Dickey County, North Dakota |access-date=2011-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202151843/http://www.nd.gov/content.htm?parentCatID=83&id=County%20History |archive-date=2015-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickey, George}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnes County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dakota Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|George Dickey (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''George H. Dickey''' (1858&ndash;1923) was an [[United States|American]] lawyer from [[Valley City, North Dakota]]. He served in the Territorial House of Representatives of the [[Dakota Territory]] Legislative Assembly in 1881-1882.<ref>[http://legis.state.sd.us/historical/LegislatorDetail.aspx?MemberID=3245 South Dakota Legislature-Historical Detail-Legislator Information-George Dickey]</ref> [[Dickey County, North Dakota]] is named in his honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nd.gov/content.htm?parentCatID=83&id=County%20History |title=Dickey County, North Dakota |access-date=2011-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202151843/http://www.nd.gov/content.htm?parentCatID=83&id=County%20History |archive-date=2015-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickey, George}}\n[[Category:1858 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnes County, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dakota Territorial Legislature]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n{{NorthDakota-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1881-1882 \u2192 1881\u20131882", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_H._Dickey"}
{"title_page": "Adamstown, Pitcairn Islands", "text_new": "{{short description|Capital and only settlement of the Pitcairn Islands}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name      = Adamstown\n|official_name  = \n|other_name     =\n|native_name =  Adamstaun ([[Pitkern language|Pitkern]])\n|nickname  = \n|settlement_type = <!-- for example city, town, village etc -->\n|total_type = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline  = Adamstown1.jpg\n|imagesize   = 300px\n|image_caption  = View of Adamstown\n|image_flag  = \n|flag_size =\n|image_seal  = \n|seal_size   =\n|image_shield   =\n|shield_size  =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map  =Map of Pitcairn Islands 2.png\n|mapsize = \n|map_caption  = Location of Adamstown\n|image_map1 =\n|mapsize1  = \n|map_caption1 = \n|image_dot_map =\n|dot_mapsize   =\n|dot_map_caption =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[Pitcairn Islands]]\n|subdivision_type1 = Sovereign State\n|subdivision_name1  = United Kingdom\n|subdivision_type2      = Island\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Geography of the Pitcairn Islands|Pitcairn]]\n\n<!-- Smaller parts (e.g. boroughs of a city) and seat of government -->\n|seat_type              =\n|seat    =\n|parts_type             =\n|parts_style  = <!-- =list (for list), coll (for collapsed list), para (for paragraph format)\n      Default is list if up to 5 items, coll if more than 5-->\n|parts                  = <!-- parts text, or header for parts list -->\n|p1                     =\n|p2                     = <!-- etc. up to p50: for separate parts to be listed--> \n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        = No local government. Administered by government of the [[Pitcairn Islands]]\n|leader_title           = [[Mayor of the Pitcairn Islands]]\n|leader_name            = [[Charlene Warren-Peu]] \n|leader_title1          =  \n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, to display imperial  before metric-->\n|area_footnotes           = <ref>Area of the island of Pitcairn</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 4.6\n|area_land_km2            = 4.6\n|area_water_km2           =\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_sq_mi          =\n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n|area_water_percent       =\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 330\n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_max_m            = \n|elevation_max_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m            = \n|elevation_min_ft           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of  =2019\n|population_footnotes  =\n|population_note =\n|population_total   =50\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone   = \n|utc_offset  = \n|timezone_DST  = \n|utc_offset_DST = \n|coor_type  = <!-- can be used to specify what the coordinates refer to -->\n|coordinates            = {{coord|25|4|S|130|6|W|type:city_region:PN|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type=  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code   =\n|area_code   =\n|blank_name = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank_info = [[Tropical rainforest climate|Af]]\n|website   = \n|footnotes  = \n}}\n\n'''Adamstown''' is the [[Capital (political)|capital]] of, and the only settlement on, the [[Pitcairn Islands]].\n\n==Overview==\nAdamstown has a population of 50, which is the entire population of the Pitcairn Islands. All the other islands in the group are uninhabited. Adamstown is where most residents eat, drink and sleep, while they grow food in other areas of the island.<ref>[http://www.lareau.org/pitc.html www.lareau.org/pitc.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060725000352/http://www.lareau.org/pitc.html |date=July 25, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAdamstown is [[List of national capitals by population|the second smallest capital in the world by population]]. It has access to [[television]], [[Satellite Internet access|satellite internet]], and a [[telephone]]; however, the main means of communication remains the [[ham radio]]. The \"Hill of Difficulty\" connects the island's jetty to the town.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of the Pitcairn Islands|Mutiny on the Bounty}}\nThe [[history]] of the [[Pitcairn Islands]] begins with the settlement of the islands by [[Polynesians]] in the 11th century. The Polynesians established a culture that flourished for four centuries and then vanished. Pitcairn was settled again in 1790 by a group of [[United Kingdom|British]] mutineers on [[HMS Bounty|HMS ''Bounty'']] and [[Tahiti]]ans. Adamstown is named for the last surviving mutineer, [[John Adams (mutineer)|John Adams]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Geography of the Pitcairn Islands}}\nThe settlement is located on the central-north side of the island of Pitcairn, facing the [[Pacific Ocean]] and close to the [[Bounty Bay]], the only seaport of the island.\n\n===Climate===\n\nAdamstown has a [[tropical rainforest climate]] under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system. The hamlet features a wet, warm climate averaging {{convert|67|in|mm|disp=flip|abbr=on}} of rain a year. The wettest month is July and temperatures do not vary significantly throughout the year.\n\n{{Weather box|location = Adamstown\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 31.7\n|Feb record high C = 32.4\n|Mar record high C = 33.3\n|Apr record high C = 30.7\n|May record high C = 29.1\n|Jun record high C = 31.3\n|Jul record high C = 26.7\n|Aug record high C = 26.7\n|Sep record high C = 25.7\n|Oct record high C = 27.2\n|Nov record high C = 27.6\n|Dec record high C = 29.3\n|year record high C = 33.3\n|Jan high C = 28\n|Feb high C = 28\n|Mar high C = 28\n|Apr high C = 26\n|May high C = 25\n|Jun high C = 23\n|Jul high C = 22\n|Aug high C = 22\n|Sep high C = 23\n|Oct high C = 24\n|Nov high C = 26\n|Dec high C = 27\n|year high C = 27.4\n|Jan mean C = 25.0\n|Feb mean C = 25.5\n|Mar mean C = 25.0\n|Apr mean C = 23.5\n|May mean C = 22.5\n|Jun mean C = 21.0\n|Jul mean C = 20.0\n|Aug mean C = 20.0\n|Sep mean C = 20.5\n|Oct mean C = 21.0\n|Nov mean C = 22.5\n|Dec mean C = 24.0\n|Jan low C = 22\n|Feb low C = 23\n|Mar low C = 22\n|Apr low C = 21\n|May low C = 20\n|Jun low C = 19\n|Jul low C = 18\n|Aug low C = 18\n|Sep low C = 18\n|Oct low C = 18\n|Nov low C = 19\n|Dec low C = 21\n|year low C = 19.7\n|Jan record low C = 20\n|Feb record low C = 20\n|Mar record low C = 20\n|Apr record low C = 18\n|May record low C = 17\n|Jun record low C = 14\n|Jul record low C = 14\n|Aug record low C = 14\n|Sep record low C = 15\n|Oct record low C = 15\n|Nov record low C = 17\n|Dec record low C = 18\n|year record low C = 14\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm = 120\n|Feb rain mm = 140\n|Mar rain mm = 120\n|Apr rain mm = 155\n|May rain mm = 130\n|Jun rain mm = 155\n|Jul rain mm = 150\n|Aug rain mm = 125\n|Sep rain mm = 140\n|Oct rain mm = 135\n|Nov rain mm = 120\n|Dec rain mm = 165\n|Jan rain days = 14\n|Feb rain days = 13\n|Mar rain days = 13\n|Apr rain days = 12\n|May rain days = 11\n|Jun rain days = 11\n|Jul rain days = 11\n|Aug rain days = 12\n|Sep rain days = 12\n|Oct rain days = 13\n|Nov rain days = 14\n|Dec rain days = 